 Matthias Rhoads as James\n* [[Diana Zubiri]] as [[Freyja|Freya]]\n* [[Fabio Ide]]<ref name=\"cast2\"/> as [[Baldr|Baldur]]\n* [[Natalia Moon]] as [[Frigg]]\n* [[Sheena Halili]]<ref name=\"cast3\">{{cite web|URL=https://www.bulgaronline.com/single-post/2018/07/10/ALDEN-AT-CO-STAR-HULI-SA-AKTO-SA-TENT |title=Nagbibihis na raw nang maabutan, Maine... Alden At Co-star, Huli Sa Akto Sa Tent |date=July 10, 2018 |author=Miralles, Nitz |accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> as Janice\n*Luri Vincent Nalus<ref name=\"cast3\"/> as Dennis\n* Michelle Dee<ref name=\"cast3\"/> as Gwen's boss\n* [[Chariz Solomon]] as Cynthia\n* [[John Feir]] as a construction worker\n* [[Pekto]] as Ringgo\n* [[Rob Moya]] as a construction worker\n* [[Kevin Santos]] as James\n* [[Carlos Agassi]] as Arvin\n* [[Sophie Albert]] as [[Edda]]\n* [[Glaiza de Castro]] as Ena<ref name=\"cast4\">{{cite web|URL=https://m.facebook.com/SolidKapusoLU/photos/a.526309037420254/2067978339919975/? |title=Abangan ang mga Sang'gre ng Encantadia sa 'Victor Magtanggol' soon. |accessdate=September 14, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Kylie Padilla]] as Ami<ref name=\"cast4\"/>\n* [[Gabbi Garcia]] as Lena<ref name=\"cast4\"/>\n* [[Sanya Lopez]] as Aya<ref name=\"cast4\"/>\n* [[Pen Medina]] as Alcala\n* Janice Hung as [[Gunnlod]]\n* Ian Ignacio as [[Thrym]]\n* Tonio Quiazon as a gun smuggler\n* Noel Urbano as the voice of [[Nidhogg]] and [[Ratatoskr]]\n\n==Production==\n[[GMA Network (company)|GMA Network]] tasked writers to come up for a television series based on [[Norse mythology]].<ref>{{cite web|URL=https://www.msn.com/en-ph/news/other/konsepto-at-istorya-ng-victor-magtanggol-inspired-ng-norse-mythology/vi-AAzYdE8 |title=Konsepto at istorya ng 'Victor Magtanggol,' inspired ng Norse mythology |trans-title=Concept and story in 'Victor Magtanggol' inspired from Norse mythology|accessdate=July 13, 2018|language=Filipino}}</ref> Jules Katanyag, concept creator of ''Victor Magtanggol'' described what he and other writers came up as \"best reflects the Filipino condition,\" which is that of uncertainty.<ref name=notthor>{{cite web|title=\u2018Victor Magtanggol\u2019 based on Norse mythology, not Marvel\u2019s Thor, says creator |url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/282799/victor-magtanggol-based-norse-mythology-not-marvels-thor-says-creator |accessdate=July 14, 2018 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=July 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Victor Magtanggol'' is set in present-day Philippines, after several [[Norse deities]] including Thor died following Ragnar\u00f6k, a series of catastrophic events in the [[Norse Mythology]].<ref name=notthor/> Part of the series was also shot outside of the Philippines.<ref name=\"Alden\"/>\n\nThe [[theme song]] \"Superhero Mo,\" is a collaboration between Alden Richards and hip-hop group, [[Ex Battalion]]. The later composed the song. A [[lyric video]] for the song was released by [[GMA Music]] on May 28, 2018.<ref name=\"collab\">{{cite web|author=Padayhag, Michelle Joy |title=Alden Richards collaborates with Ex Batallion for \u2018Victor Magtanggol\u2019 theme song |url=http://cebudailynews.inquirer.net/177390/alden-richards-collaborates-ex-batallion-victor-magtanggol-theme-song |accessdate=July 18, 2018 |work=Cebu Daily News |publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=May 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Ratings==\nAccording to [[AGB Nielsen Philippines]]' Nationwide Urban Television Audience Measurement People in Television Homes, the pilot episode of ''Victor Magtanggol'' earned a 12.4% rating.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/FagutaoJimmuel/status/1024226074438164482?|title=Jeraska Fagutao 12 on Twitter: \"Victor Magtanggol managed to acquire one of the highest pilot episodes of GMA Telebabad to date and it is expected to topple Ang Probinsyano soon or maybe on {{sic|it's|nolink=y}} brilliant pilot week.\" |date=July 31, 2018 |accessdate=May 15, 2019}}</ref> While the final episode scored an 11.1% rating.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/GoodThing193/status/1064388085083910144? |title=Yera Calma on Twitter: \"AGB Nielsen NUTAM People ratings November 16, 2018 (Friday )\" |date=November 19, 2018 |accessdate=May 15, 2019}}</ref> The series got its highest rating on August 1, 2018 with a 12.7% rating.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Showbiz_Polls/status/1024512227259211776?|title=Entertainment Uptake on Twitter |date=August 1, 2018 |accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Awards\n! Category\n! Recipient\n! Result\n! Ref.\n|-\n| 2019\n| [[33rd PMPC Star Awards for Television]]\n| Best Drama Actor\n| Alden Richards\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/146277/33rd-star-awards-for-television-names-tv-queens-pmpc-bares-nominees |title=33rd Star Awards for Television names TV Queens; PMPC bares nominees |work=Pep.ph |language=en |author=Dimaculangan, Jocelyn |date=September 22, 2019 |accessdate=September 23, 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official site|http://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/tv/victor_magtanggol}}\n* {{IMDB title|8760072}}\n\n[[Category:GMA Network drama series]]\n[[Category:Philippine drama television series]]\n[[Category:2018 Philippine television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2018 Philippine television series endings]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Fantaserye and telefantasya]]\n[[Category:Superhero television programs]]\n[[Category:Filipino-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series based on Norse mythology]]\n\n{{Philippines-tv-prog-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hotwiki", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProduction:fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Victor_Magtanggol"}
{"title_page": "Ruth Dudley Edwards", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish historian, biographer and crime fiction author}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n'''Ruth Dudley Edwards''' (born 24 May 1944, in [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]) is an Irish revisionist historian and writer of biography, crime and historical fiction.<ref>Dudley Edwards, Ruth. \"Confessions of an Irish Revisionist\" in (Homberger, Eric; Charmley, John ed.  \"The Troubled face of biography\") New York : St. Martin's Press, (1988). {{ISBN|9780312013295}}.</ref><ref>[{{Cite tweet |user=ruthde |number=668816347774754816 |date = 23 November 2015 |title=Every historian should be a revisionist, i.e. someone who constantly revises opinions in the light of new evidence  }}]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indymedia.ie/article/76386|title=Ruth Dudley Edwards urges Queens University audience to ignore 'well known eccentric' - Indymedia Ireland|website=www.indymedia.ie}}</ref> One of several positions she holds is columnist with the Irish ''[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]''.\n\n==Background==\nDudley Edwards was born and brought up in [[Dublin]] and educated at [[University College Dublin]] (UCD), [[Girton College, Cambridge]], and [[Wolfson College, Cambridge]]. Her father was the Irish historian Professor [[Robert Dudley Edwards]]. Her brother [[Owen Dudley Edwards]] is a historian at the [[University of Edinburgh]]. Her sister, Mary, is deceased <ref>https://notices.irishtimes.com/death/dudley-edwards-mary/42714301</ref>. In 1965, she married a fellow UCD graduate, the journalist [[Patrick Cosgrave]]; they later divorced.\n\nHer grandmother, [[Bridget Dudley Edwards]], was an [[Dublin Women's Suffrage Association|Irish suffragette]] and a member of [[Cumann na mBan]], a women's organisation designed to support the [[Irish Volunteers]]. Members of Cumann na mBan gathered intelligence, transported arms, nursed wounded men, provided safe houses, and organised support for IRA men in prison. They also boosted attendance at election rallies, funerals and protest marches. In 1922 the organisation overwhelmingly rejected the Treaty.\n\n==Works==\nHer non-fiction books include ''An Atlas of Irish History'', ''[[James Connolly]]'', ''[[Victor Gollancz]]: A Biography'' (winner of the [[James Tait Black Memorial Prize]]), ''The Pursuit of Reason: [[The Economist]] 1843\u20131993'', ''The Faithful Tribe: An Intimate Portrait of the Loyal Institutions'' (shortlisted for [[Channel 4]]/[[The House Politico]]'s Book of the Year) and ''Newspapermen: [[Hugh Cudlipp]], [[Cecil Harmsworth King|Cecil King]] and the glory days of Fleet Street''. Her ''[[Patrick Pearse]]: The Triumph of Failure'' (winner of the National University of Ireland Prize for Historical Research), first published in 1977, was reissued in 2006 by [[Irish Academic Press]].\n\nIn 2009 she published ''Aftermath: The Omagh Bombings and the Families' Pursuit of Justice'', a book about the civil case that was won on 8 June 2009 against the [[Omagh bombing#Prosecutions and court cases|Omagh bombers]]. ''The Faithful Tribe'' was criticised by [[Ulster Protestant]] journalist Susan McKay as \"sentimental and blinkered\",<ref>Susan McKay ''Northern Protestants'' p.138</ref> but the ''[[New Statesman]]'' contributor Stephen Howe described it as \"engrossing and illuminating\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/international-politics/2013/07/south-africas-military-meltdown|title=South Africa\u2019s military meltdown|website=www.newstatesman.com|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref> and the ''[[Irish Independent]]'' journalist [[John A. Murphy]] described it as \"enormously readable, entertaining and informative\", but \"[her argument] 'extremely disingenuous'\", and he quotes Shakespeare, '[[The lady doth protest too much, methinks]]', when describing one of her counter-arguments as 'exaggerated'. He added \"Historically in Ireland, Protestant 'liberties' tended to mean Protestant 'privilege,' and many Protestants (even including some United Irishmen) doubted whether Roman Catholics were constitutionally capax libertatis capable of appreciating or enjoying liberty at all, because of Roman tyranny and priest-craft. In short, the Orange Protestant is still benightedly living in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries: the Southern Catholic, whatever his past intolerances, has moved on.\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/woman/celeb-news/the-orangeman-as-decent-skin-26260130.html|title=The Orangeman as decent skin|website=Independent.ie|language=en|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref> In 2016 she published ''The Seven: The Lives and Legacies of the Founding Fathers of the Irish Republic'' (Oneworld), a re-examination of the [[Easter Rising]], addressing the fundamental questions and myths surrounding the 1916 leaders.\n\nAlso a crime fiction writer, her novels include: ''Corridors of Death'', ''The Saint Valentine's Day Murders'', ''The English School of Murder'', ''Clubbed to Death'', ''Matricide at St. Martha's'', ''Ten Lords A-Leaping'', ''Murder in a Cathedral'', ''Publish and Be Murdered'', ''Anglo-Irish Murders'', ''Carnage on the Committee'', ''Murdering Americans'', and ''Killing the Emperors''.\n\n==Positions==\n===Criticism of Ken Loach===\nFollowing the Cannes prize announcement, for ''[[The Wind That Shakes the Barley (film)|The Wind That Shakes the Barley]]'', Ruth Dudley Edwards wrote in the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' on 30 May 2006 that [[Ken Loach|Loach]]'s political viewpoint \"requires the portrayal of the British as sadists and the Irish as romantic, idealistic resistance fighters who take to violence only because there is no other self-respecting course,\"<ref name=\"Dudley Edwards Mail\">[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-388256/Why-does-Ken-Loach-loathe-country-much.html \"Why does Ken Loach loathe his country so much?\"] ''The Daily Mail'', 30 May 2006</ref> and attacked his career in an article.<ref name=\"Loach in Indymedia\">[http://ireland.indymedia.org/article/76396 \"Ken Loach hits back at English tabloids\"] Indymedia Ireland, 1 June 2006</ref> The following week, Edwards continued her attack in ''[[The Guardian]]'', admitting that her first article was written without seeing the film (which at that stage had only been shown at Cannes), and asserting that she would never see it \"because I can't stand its sheer predictability.\"<ref name=\"Dudley Edwards Guardian\">[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/jun/06/whataboutmakingblackandta \"What about making Black and Tans: the movie?\"] ''The Guardian'', 6 June 2006</ref>\n\n===Unionism and Irish unification===\nDudley Edwards has stated that she is \"not in principle against [[Irish unification]]\".<ref>[http://www.independent.ie/opinion/analysis/irishness-can-truly-be-a--many-splendoured-thing-1428412.html Irishness can truly be a many splendoured thing], [[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]], 6 July 2008, p 22</ref>\n\n==Positions held==\n*Chairwoman, [[British Association for Irish Studies]] 1985\u201393\n*Member, Executive Committee of the [[British-Irish Association]] 1982\u201393\n*Member, Executive Committee of the [[Crime Writers' Association]] 1995\u201399\n*Member of Management Committee of the [[Society of Authors]] 1996\u201399\n*Elected to [[Detection Club]] 1996\n*[[Board of directors|Director]], [[Centre for Social Cohesion]] (2009\u20132013)<ref name=\"CompHouse\">{{Cite web|url=http://wck2.companieshouse.gov.uk/75e305b0efbac0172978126469c8b941/wcprodorder?ft=1|title=Failure Page|website=wck2.companieshouse.gov.uk|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/ruth-dudley-edwards/ Ruth Dudley Edwards] at the ''[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]''\n* [http://www.ruthdudleyedwards.co.uk/ Personal website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dudley Edwards, Ruth}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from County Dublin]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Girton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Wolfson College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Sunday Independent (Ireland) people]]\n[[Category:James Tait Black Memorial Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:Irish women novelists]]\n[[Category:Irish columnists]]\n[[Category:Irish historians]]\n[[Category:Irish women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Irish women academics]]\n[[Category:Irish women journalists]]\n[[Category:Women columnists]]\n[[Category:Revisionism (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Women historians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish historian, biographer and crime fiction author}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}}\n'''Ruth Dudley Edwards''' (born 24 May 1944, in [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]) is an Irish revisionist historian and writer of history, biography and crime fiction.<ref>Dudley Edwards, Ruth. \"Confessions of an Irish Revisionist\" in (Homberger, Eric; Charmley, John ed.  \"The Troubled face of biography\") New York : St. Martin's Press, (1988). {{ISBN|9780312013295}}.</ref><ref>[{{Cite tweet |user=ruthde |number=668816347774754816 |date = 23 November 2015 |title=Every historian should be a revisionist, i.e. someone who constantly revises opinions in the light of new evidence  }}]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indymedia.ie/article/76386|title=Ruth Dudley Edwards urges Queens University audience to ignore 'well known eccentric' - Indymedia Ireland|website=www.indymedia.ie}}</ref> One of several positions she holds is columnist with the Irish ''[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]''.\n\n==Background==\nDudley Edwards was born and brought up in [[Dublin]] and educated at [[University College Dublin]] (UCD), [[Girton College, Cambridge]], and [[Wolfson College, Cambridge]]. Her father was the Irish historian Professor [[Robert Dudley Edwards]]. Her brother [[Owen Dudley Edwards]] is a historian at the [[University of Edinburgh]]. Her sister, Mary, is deceased <ref>https://notices.irishtimes.com/death/dudley-edwards-mary/42714301</ref>. In 1965, she married a fellow UCD graduate, the journalist [[Patrick Cosgrave]]; they later divorced.\n\nHer grandmother, [[Bridget Dudley Edwards]], was an [[Dublin Women's Suffrage Association|Irish suffragette]] and a member of [[Cumann na mBan]], a women's organisation designed to support the [[Irish Volunteers]]. Members of Cumann na mBan gathered intelligence, transported arms, nursed wounded men, provided safe houses, and organised support for IRA men in prison. They also boosted attendance at election rallies, funerals and protest marches. In 1922 the organisation overwhelmingly rejected the Treaty.\n\n==Works==\nHer non-fiction books include ''An Atlas of Irish History'', ''[[James Connolly]]'', ''[[Victor Gollancz]]: A Biography'' (winner of the [[James Tait Black Memorial Prize]]), ''The Pursuit of Reason: [[The Economist]] 1843\u20131993'', ''The Faithful Tribe: An Intimate Portrait of the Loyal Institutions'' (shortlisted for [[Channel 4]]/[[The House Politico]]'s Book of the Year) and ''Newspapermen: [[Hugh Cudlipp]], [[Cecil Harmsworth King|Cecil King]] and the glory days of Fleet Street''. Her ''[[Patrick Pearse]]: The Triumph of Failure'' (winner of the National University of Ireland Prize for Historical Research), first published in 1977, was reissued in 2006 by [[Irish Academic Press]].\n\nIn 2009 she published ''Aftermath: The Omagh Bombings and the Families' Pursuit of Justice'', a book about the civil case that was won on 8 June 2009 against the [[Omagh bombing#Prosecutions and court cases|Omagh bombers]]. ''The Faithful Tribe'' was criticised by [[Ulster Protestant]] journalist Susan McKay as \"sentimental and blinkered\",<ref>Susan McKay ''Northern Protestants'' p.138</ref> but the ''[[New Statesman]]'' contributor Stephen Howe described it as \"engrossing and illuminating\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/international-politics/2013/07/south-africas-military-meltdown|title=South Africa\u2019s military meltdown|website=www.newstatesman.com|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref> and the ''[[Irish Independent]]'' journalist [[John A. Murphy]] described it as \"enormously readable, entertaining and informative\", but \"[her argument] 'extremely disingenuous'\", and he quotes Shakespeare, '[[The lady doth protest too much, methinks]]', when describing one of her counter-arguments as 'exaggerated'. He added \"Historically in Ireland, Protestant 'liberties' tended to mean Protestant 'privilege,' and many Protestants (even including some United Irishmen) doubted whether Roman Catholics were constitutionally capax libertatis capable of appreciating or enjoying liberty at all, because of Roman tyranny and priest-craft. In short, the Orange Protestant is still benightedly living in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries: the Southern Catholic, whatever his past intolerances, has moved on.\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/woman/celeb-news/the-orangeman-as-decent-skin-26260130.html|title=The Orangeman as decent skin|website=Independent.ie|language=en|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref> In 2016 she published ''The Seven: The Lives and Legacies of the Founding Fathers of the Irish Republic'' (Oneworld), a re-examination of the [[Easter Rising]], addressing the fundamental questions and myths surrounding the 1916 leaders.\n\nAlso a crime fiction writer, her novels include: ''Corridors of Death'', ''The Saint Valentine's Day Murders'', ''The English School of Murder'', ''Clubbed to Death'', ''Matricide at St. Martha's'', ''Ten Lords A-Leaping'', ''Murder in a Cathedral'', ''Publish and Be Murdered'', ''Anglo-Irish Murders'', ''Carnage on the Committee'', ''Murdering Americans'', and ''Killing the Emperors''.\n\n==Positions==\n===Criticism of Ken Loach===\nFollowing the Cannes prize announcement, for ''[[The Wind That Shakes the Barley (film)|The Wind That Shakes the Barley]]'', Ruth Dudley Edwards wrote in the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' on 30 May 2006 that [[Ken Loach|Loach]]'s political viewpoint \"requires the portrayal of the British as sadists and the Irish as romantic, idealistic resistance fighters who take to violence only because there is no other self-respecting course,\"<ref name=\"Dudley Edwards Mail\">[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-388256/Why-does-Ken-Loach-loathe-country-much.html \"Why does Ken Loach loathe his country so much?\"] ''The Daily Mail'', 30 May 2006</ref> and attacked his career in an article.<ref name=\"Loach in Indymedia\">[http://ireland.indymedia.org/article/76396 \"Ken Loach hits back at English tabloids\"] Indymedia Ireland, 1 June 2006</ref> The following week, Edwards continued her attack in ''[[The Guardian]]'', admitting that her first article was written without seeing the film (which at that stage had only been shown at Cannes), and asserting that she would never see it \"because I can't stand its sheer predictability.\"<ref name=\"Dudley Edwards Guardian\">[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2006/jun/06/whataboutmakingblackandta \"What about making Black and Tans: the movie?\"] ''The Guardian'', 6 June 2006</ref>\n\n===Unionism and Irish unification===\nDudley Edwards has stated that she is \"not in principle against [[Irish unification]]\".<ref>[http://www.independent.ie/opinion/analysis/irishness-can-truly-be-a--many-splendoured-thing-1428412.html Irishness can truly be a many splendoured thing], [[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]], 6 July 2008, p 22</ref>\n\n==Positions held==\n*Chairwoman, [[British Association for Irish Studies]] 1985\u201393\n*Member, Executive Committee of the [[British-Irish Association]] 1982\u201393\n*Member, Executive Committee of the [[Crime Writers' Association]] 1995\u201399\n*Member of Management Committee of the [[Society of Authors]] 1996\u201399\n*Elected to [[Detection Club]] 1996\n*[[Board of directors|Director]], [[Centre for Social Cohesion]] (2009\u20132013)<ref name=\"CompHouse\">{{Cite web|url=http://wck2.companieshouse.gov.uk/75e305b0efbac0172978126469c8b941/wcprodorder?ft=1|title=Failure Page|website=wck2.companieshouse.gov.uk|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/ruth-dudley-edwards/ Ruth Dudley Edwards] at the ''[[Sunday Independent (Ireland)|Sunday Independent]]''\n* [http://www.ruthdudleyedwards.co.uk/ Personal website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dudley Edwards, Ruth}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from County Dublin]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Girton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Wolfson College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Sunday Independent (Ireland) people]]\n[[Category:James Tait Black Memorial Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:Irish women novelists]]\n[[Category:Irish columnists]]\n[[Category:Irish historians]]\n[[Category:Irish women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Irish women academics]]\n[[Category:Irish women journalists]]\n[[Category:Women columnists]]\n[[Category:Revisionism (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Women historians]]\n", "name_user": "2001:bb6:26bc:700:3c07:5e77:4b43:a65f", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruth_Dudley_Edwards"}
{"title_page": "1916 Auckland Rugby League season", "text_new": "The 1916 [[Auckland Rugby League]] season was the 8th year of the organisation. All grades were dramatically affected by players enlisting in the war efforts. Prior to the commencement of the season it was stated in the management committee meeting that 487 players in the Auckland district alone had committed to the war effort\n.<ref>{{cite news\n| title =Big Entry of Teams\n| page =7\n| publisher =Auckland Star, Volume XLVII, Issue 107\n| date = 1916-05-04\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19160505.2.101\n| accessdate = 2019-12-09}}</ref> Teams were filled with older players and juniors. The [[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu]] senior team as was noted at their committee meeting featured \u201conly three men eligible for military service..., and these were all registered and waiting to be called up. Of the remainder, six were married men with families, two were permanent force men, and four were under military age\u201d.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Otahuhu Club\n| page = 4\n| work = New Zealand Herald |volume=LIII |issue=16225\n| date = 1916-05-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19160510.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-14}}</ref> \n\nDespite this attendances were still good, with the mid season match between [[City Rovers]] and [[Grafton Athletic]] at [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]] attracting 3,000 spectators. While the Round 7 fixtures at [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]] drew the same number of spectators and 4,000 attending the round 8 matches. All the gate takings were donated to the Children's Hospital Ward Equipment Fund.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =City Defeats North Shore\n| page = 8\n| work = New Zealand Herald |volume=LIII |issue=16277\n| date = 1916-07-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19160710.2.79\n| accessdate = 2019-08-14}}</ref> The final round saw over 4,000 attend Victoria Park where [[City Rovers]] won the title with a 14 points to 10 win over [[Grafton Athletic]].<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Senior Championship/Won by City Rovers/City Defeats Grafton/North Shore V Newton/Ponsonby V Otahuhu\n| page =8\n| work = New Zealand Herald |volume=LIII |issue=16289\n| date = 1916-07-24\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19160724.2.61.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-14}}</ref> City also went on to win the end of season knockout Roope Rooster competition. \n\nOwing to the effects of the war on playing strength there were no representative matches, though [[City Rovers]] did play the Lower Waikato in two exhibition fixtures (home and away), and [[Richmond Bulldogs|Richmond Rovers]] and Thames Old Boys (based in Auckland) traveled to [[Thames]] to play a match at the season end.\n\n===End of Season Report===\nAt the end of the 1916 season a report was made on the season and it was presented to the [[Auckland Rugby League]] annual meeting in May, 1917. It stated that the playing ranks had been severely depleted over the past season as over 600 players had joined the ranks of the military to fight in the first world war. There were 42 teams in total to compete across six grades (7 in the senior grade, 5 in second grade, 9 in third grade, 7 in the fourth grade, 8 in the fifth grade, and 6 in the sixth grade). Fourteen clubs were affiliated to the Auckland Rugby League with over 800 players in total. The Mangere, Remuera, and [[Northcote Tigers|Northcote]] clubs withdrew from the competition due to so many of their players going to war.\n\nSignificantly they secured the option of the Chinamen's gardens just off Stanley Street and this was to later be turned into [[Carlaw Park]].<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Auckland Rugby League/Past Season Reviewed\n| page =8\n| work = New Zealand Herald |volume=LIV |issue=16526\n| date = 1917-04-30\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19170430.2.71.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-14}}</ref>\n\nIt was suggested that the newly-formed Garrison Artillery Club enter a first grade team however as there were already 6 teams competing there was a fear that it would weaken the existing teams. [[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu]] asked for [[Auckland Rugby League]] to request a special Saturday afternoon \u201ctrain to be run to bring players, spectators and the general public to [[Otahuhu]] or Saturday afternoons\u201d during the season.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Arrangements for Saturday\n| page =4\n| work = New Zealand Herald |volume=LIII\n| date = 1916-05-10\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19160510.2.9.1| accessdate = 2019-08-14}}</ref>\n\n{{s-start}}\n        {{s-bef|before=[[1915 Auckland Rugby League season|1915]]}}\n        {{s-ttl|title=8th [[Auckland Rugby League]] season\n        |years=1916}}\n        {{s-aft|after=[[1917 Auckland Rugby League season|1917]]}}\n        {{end}}\n\n==First Grade Championship==\nThirty matches were played during the season with the 20 being played at [[Victoria Park, Auckland|Victoria Park]]. The Devonport Domain hosted the 5 North Shore Albions home matches, while [[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu]] hosted 5 matches.\n\n===Final Standings and Fixtures===\n{|\n|-\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=175 |Team\n!width=20 abbr=\"Played\" |Pld\n!width=20 abbr=\"Won\" |W\n!width=20 abbr=\"Drawn\" |D\n!width=20 abbr=\"Lost\" |L\n!width=20 abbr=\"For\" |F\n!width=20 abbr=\"Against\" |A\n!width=20 abbr=\"Points\" |Pts\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[City Rovers]]\n|10||8||1||1||112||57||'''17'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[North Shore Albions]]\n|10||7||1||2||134||57||'''15'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Grafton Athletic]]\n|10||5||0||5||101||85||'''10'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]]\n|10||4||1||5||101||86||'''9'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu]]\n|10||2||1||6||45||95||'''5'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Newton Rangers]]\n|10||2|