{"title_page": "Crisaborole", "text_new": "{{Infobox drug\n| IUPAC_name = 4-[(1-Hydroxy-1,3-dihydro-2,1-benzoxaborol-5-yl)oxy]benzonitrile\n| image = Crisaborole.svg\n| width = \n\n<!--Clinical data -->\n| tradename = Eucrisa, {{IPAc-en|j|u\u02d0|\u02c8|k|r|\u026a|s|\u0259}} {{respell|yoo|KRIS|\u0259}}\n| MedlinePlus = \n| licence_EU = \n| licence_US = \n| pregnancy_AU = \n| pregnancy_US = \n| pregnancy_category = \n| legal_CA = Rx-only\n| legal_US = Rx-only\n| legal_status = \n| routes_of_administration = [[Topical medication|Topical]] ([[Topical medication#Ointment|ointment]])\n\n<!--Identifiers -->\n| CAS_number = 906673-24-3\n| CAS_supplemental = \n| ATCvet = \n| ATC_prefix = D11\n| ATC_suffix = AH06\n| ATC_supplemental = \n| PubChem = 44591583\n| PubChemSubstance = \n| IUPHAR_ligand = \n| DrugBank = DB05219\n| ChemSpiderID = 24701949\n| UNII = Q2R47HGR7P\n| KEGG = D10873\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEBI = 134677\n| ChEMBL = \n| NIAID_ChemDB = \n| synonyms = \n\n<!--Chemical data -->\n| C=14 | H=10 | B=1 | N=1 | O=3\n| molecular_weight = 251.045 g/mol\n| SMILES = B1(c2ccc(cc2CO1)Oc3ccc(cc3)C#N)O\n| StdInChI = 1S/C14H10BNO3/c16-8-10-1-3-12(4-2-10)19-13-5-6-14-11(7-13)9-18-15(14)17/h1-7,17H,9H2\n| StdInChI_comment = \n| StdInChIKey = USZAGAREISWJDP-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n}}\n\n'''Crisaborole''', sold under the brand name '''Eucrisa''', is a [[nonsteroidal]] [[topical medication]] used for the treatment of mild-to-moderate [[atopic dermatitis]] (eczema) in people two years or older.<ref name=\"FDA approval\">{{cite web | title = FDA Approves Eucrisa for Eczema | url = https://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/ucm533371.htm | publisher = U.S. Food and Drug Administration | date = 14 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"PI\">{{cite web | title=Eucrisa (crisaborole) Ointment, 2%, for Topical Use. Full Prescribing Information | url = http://labeling.pfizer.com/ShowLabeling.aspx?id=5331 | publisher = Anacor Pharmaceuticals, Inc. Palo Alto, CA 94303 USA | accessdate = 17 December 2016}}</ref> It was approved by U.S. Food and Drug Administration on Dec 14, 2016<ref>{{cite press release | url = https://www.fda.gov/newsevents/newsroom/pressannouncements/ucm533371.htm | title = FDA approves Eucrisa for eczema | date = December 14, 2016 | publisher = U.S. Food and Drug Administration}}</ref> and June 6, 2018 by Health Canada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hpr-rps.hres.ca/reg-content/regulatory-decision-summary-detail.php?lang=en&linkID=RDS00420|title=Regulatory Decision Summary - Eucrisa - Health Canada|last=Government of Canada|website=Health Canada|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914204206/https://hpr-rps.hres.ca/reg-content/regulatory-decision-summary-detail.php?lang=en&linkID=RDS00420|archive-date=2019-09-14|access-date=2019-09-14|date=2014-10-23}}</ref>\n\n==Side effects==\nAt the site of application, crisaborole may cause burning or stinging. Rarely, there may be an [[Allergy|allergic reaction]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdf.hres.ca/dpd_pm/00045835.PDF|title=PRODUCT MONOGRAPH|date=2018-06-07|website=Government of Canada|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407223013/https://pdf.hres.ca/dpd_pm/00045835.PDF|archive-date=2019-04-07|url-status=live|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Pharmacology==\n\n===Pharmacodynamics===\nCrisaborole is a [[phosphodiesterase-4 inhibitor]], mainly acting on [[PDE4B|phosphodiesterase 4B]] (PDE4B), which causes inflammation.<ref name=\"Moustafa\" /> Chemically, crisaborole is a [[phenoxybenzoxaborole]].<ref name=\"Moustafa\" /> Inhibition of PDE4B appears to suppress the release of [[tumor necrosis factor alpha]] (TNF\u03b1), [[interleukin-12]] (IL-12), [[Interleukin 23|IL-23]] and other [[cytokines]], proteins believed to be involved in the immune response and inflammation.<ref name=\"Moustafa\" />\n\n==Chemistry==\nCrisaborole (chemical name: 4-[(1-hydroxy-1,3-dihydro-2,1-benzoxaborol-5-yl)oxy]benzonitrile) is a member of the class of benzoxaboroles characterized by the presence of a [[boronic acid]] hemiester with a phenolic ether and a nitrile.<ref>{{cite web|title=WHO Drug Information, Vol. 29, No. 3, 2015. International Nonproprietary Names for Pharmaceutical Substances (INN). Recommended International Nonproprietary Names: List 74|url=http://www.who.int/medicines/publications/druginformation/innlists/RL74.pdf|publisher=World Health Information|accessdate=26 April 2016|page=391}}</ref> Crisaborole crystallizes into two [[polymorphism (materials science)|polymorphs]] that differ in the conformation of the oxaborole ring. A [[cocrystal]] with [[4,4'-Bipyridine|4,4'-bipyridine]] has been prepared and studied by [[X-ray crystallography]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Campillo-Alvarado|first=Gonzalo|last2=Didden|first2=Tighe D.|last3=Oburn|first3=Shalisa M.|last4=Swenson|first4=Dale C.|last5=MacGillivray|first5=Leonard R.|date=2018|title=Exploration of Solid Forms of Crisaborole: Crystal Engineering Identifies Polymorphism in Commercial Sources and Facilitates Cocrystal Formation|journal=Crystal Growth & Design|language=en|volume=18|issue=8|pages=4416\u20134419|doi=10.1021/acs.cgd.8b00375|issn=1528-7483}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nCrisaborole was [[drug development|developed]] by [[Anacor]] Pharmaceuticals for the topical treatment of [[psoriasis]].<ref name=\"Nazarian\">{{cite journal | last1 = Nazarian | first1 = R | last2 = Weinberg | first2 = JM | title = AN-2728, a PDE4 Inhibitor for the Potential Topical Treatment of Psoriasis and Atopic Dermatitis | journal = Current Opinion in Investigational Drugs | date = November 2009 | volume = 10 | issue = 11 | pages = 1236\u201342 | pmid = 19876791}}</ref><ref name=\"Moustafa\">{{cite journal | last1 = Moustafa | first1 = F | last2 = Feldman | first2 = SR | title = A Review of Phosphodiesterase-Inhibition and the Potential Role for Phosphodiesterase 4-Inhibitors in Clinical Dermatology | journal = Dermatology Online Journal | date = 16 May 2014 | volume = 20 | issue = 5 | pages = 22608 | pmid = 24852768 | url = http://escholarship.org/uc/item/2hx1m6kv.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"Spreitzer\">{{cite journal | last1 = Spreitzer | first1 = H | title = Neue Wirkstoffe: Crisaborol | journal = \u00d6sterreichische Apotheker-Zeitung | date = 16 August 2016 | issue = 17/2016 | language = German}}</ref> During preclinical and clinical development, crisaborole was called AN2728 and PF-06930164.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crisaborole|url=http://adisinsight.springer.com/drugs/800024239|publisher=AdisInsight|accessdate=24 July 2017|language=en}}</ref>\nThe drug was assumed to be potential $2bn-a-year blockbuster, when Pfizer acquired Anacor Pharmaceuticals. However, the drug was commercially not successful, reaching only 138 Mio $ sales in 2019 <ref>{{cite web|title=Pfizer Financial Report|url=https://s21.q4cdn.com/317678438/files/doc_financials/Quarterly/2019/q4/Q4-2019-PFE-Earnings-Release.pdf|publisher=Pfizer|accessdate=9 April 2020|language=en}} </ref>.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tavaborole]] \u2013 a structurally related topical [[antifungal]] developed by Anacor\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Phosphodiesterase inhibitors}}\n\n[[Category:Ethers]]\n[[Category:Nitriles]]\n[[Category:Organoboron compounds]]\n[[Category:PDE4 inhibitors]]\n[[Category:Phosphodiesterase inhibitors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox drug\n| IUPAC_name = 4-[(1-Hydroxy-1,3-dihydro-2,1-benzoxaborol-5-yl)oxy]benzonitrile\n| image = Crisaborole.svg\n| width = \n\n<!--Clinical data -->\n| tradename = Eucrisa, {{IPAc-en|j|u\u02d0|\u02c8|k|r|\u026a|s|\u0259}} {{respell|yoo|KRIS|\u0259}}\n| MedlinePlus = \n| licence_EU = \n| licence_US = \n| pregnancy_AU = \n| pregnancy_US = \n| pregnancy_category = \n| legal_CA = Rx-only\n| legal_US = Rx-only\n| legal_status = \n| routes_of_administration = [[Topical medication|Topical]] ([[Topical medication#Ointment|ointment]])\n\n<!--Identifiers -->\n| CAS_number = 906673-24-3\n| CAS_supplemental = \n| ATCvet = \n| ATC_prefix = D11\n| ATC_suffix = AH06\n| ATC_supplemental = \n| PubChem = 44591583\n| PubChemSubstance = \n| IUPHAR_ligand = \n| DrugBank = DB05219\n| ChemSpiderID = 24701949\n| UNII = Q2R47HGR7P\n| KEGG = D10873\n| ChEBI_Ref = {{ebicite|correct|EBI}}\n| ChEBI = 134677\n| ChEMBL = \n| NIAID_ChemDB = \n| synonyms = \n\n<!--Chemical data -->\n| C=14 | H=10 | B=1 | N=1 | O=3\n| molecular_weight = 251.045 g/mol\n| SMILES = B1(c2ccc(cc2CO1)Oc3ccc(cc3)C#N)O\n| StdInChI = 1S/C14H10BNO3/c16-8-10-1-3-12(4-2-10)19-13-5-6-14-11(7-13)9-18-15(14)17/h1-7,17H,9H2\n| StdInChI_comment = \n| StdInChIKey = USZAGAREISWJDP-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n}}\n\n'''Crisaborole''', sold under the brand name '''Eucrisa''', is a [[nonsteroidal]] [[topical medication]] used for the treatment of mild-to-moderate [[atopic dermatitis]] (eczema) in people two years or older.<ref name=\"FDA approval\">{{cite web | title = FDA Approves Eucrisa for Eczema | url = https://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/ucm533371.htm | publisher = U.S. Food and Drug Administration | date = 14 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"PI\">{{cite web | title=Eucrisa (crisaborole) Ointment, 2%, for Topical Use. Full Prescribing Information | url = http://labeling.pfizer.com/ShowLabeling.aspx?id=5331 | publisher = Anacor Pharmaceuticals, Inc. Palo Alto, CA 94303 USA | accessdate = 17 December 2016}}</ref> It was approved by U.S. Food and Drug Administration on Dec 14, 2016<ref>{{cite press release | url = https://www.fda.gov/newsevents/newsroom/pressannouncements/ucm533371.htm | title = FDA approves Eucrisa for eczema | date = December 14, 2016 | publisher = U.S. Food and Drug Administration}}</ref> and June 6, 2018 by Health Canada.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hpr-rps.hres.ca/reg-content/regulatory-decision-summary-detail.php?lang=en&linkID=RDS00420|title=Regulatory Decision Summary - Eucrisa - Health Canada|last=Government of Canada|website=Health Canada|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914204206/https://hpr-rps.hres.ca/reg-content/regulatory-decision-summary-detail.php?lang=en&linkID=RDS00420|archive-date=2019-09-14|access-date=2019-09-14|date=2014-10-23}}</ref>\n\n==Side effects==\nAt the site of application, crisaborole may cause burning or stinging. Rarely, there may be an [[Allergy|allergic reaction]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pdf.hres.ca/dpd_pm/00045835.PDF|title=PRODUCT MONOGRAPH|date=2018-06-07|website=Government of Canada|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190407223013/https://pdf.hres.ca/dpd_pm/00045835.PDF|archive-date=2019-04-07|url-status=live|access-date=2019-04-07}}</ref>\n\n==Pharmacology==\n\n===Pharmacodynamics===\nCrisaborole is a [[phosphodiesterase-4 inhibitor]], mainly acting on [[PDE4B|phosphodiesterase 4B]] (PDE4B), which causes inflammation.<ref name=\"Moustafa\" /> Chemically, crisaborole is a [[phenoxybenzoxaborole]].<ref name=\"Moustafa\" /> Inhibition of PDE4B appears to suppress the release of [[tumor necrosis factor alpha]] (TNF\u03b1), [[interleukin-12]] (IL-12), [[Interleukin 23|IL-23]] and other [[cytokines]], proteins believed to be involved in the immune response and inflammation.<ref name=\"Moustafa\" />\n\n==Chemistry==\nCrisaborole (chemical name: 4-[(1-hydroxy-1,3-dihydro-2,1-benzoxaborol-5-yl)oxy]benzonitrile) is a member of the class of benzoxaboroles characterized by the presence of a [[boronic acid]] hemiester with a phenolic ether and a nitrile.<ref>{{cite web|title=WHO Drug Information, Vol. 29, No. 3, 2015. International Nonproprietary Names for Pharmaceutical Substances (INN). Recommended International Nonproprietary Names: List 74|url=http://www.who.int/medicines/publications/druginformation/innlists/RL74.pdf|publisher=World Health Information|accessdate=26 April 2016|page=391}}</ref> Crisaborole crystallizes into two [[polymorphism (materials science)|polymorphs]] that differ in the conformation of the oxaborole ring. A [[cocrystal]] with [[4,4'-Bipyridine|4,4'-bipyridine]] has been prepared and studied by [[X-ray crystallography]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Campillo-Alvarado|first=Gonzalo|last2=Didden|first2=Tighe D.|last3=Oburn|first3=Shalisa M.|last4=Swenson|first4=Dale C.|last5=MacGillivray|first5=Leonard R.|date=2018|title=Exploration of Solid Forms of Crisaborole: Crystal Engineering Identifies Polymorphism in Commercial Sources and Facilitates Cocrystal Formation|journal=Crystal Growth & Design|language=en|volume=18|issue=8|pages=4416\u20134419|doi=10.1021/acs.cgd.8b00375|issn=1528-7483}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nCrisaborole was [[drug development|developed]] by [[Anacor]] Pharmaceuticals for the topical treatment of [[psoriasis]].<ref name=\"Nazarian\">{{cite journal | last1 = Nazarian | first1 = R | last2 = Weinberg | first2 = JM | title = AN-2728, a PDE4 Inhibitor for the Potential Topical Treatment of Psoriasis and Atopic Dermatitis | journal = Current Opinion in Investigational Drugs | date = November 2009 | volume = 10 | issue = 11 | pages = 1236\u201342 | pmid = 19876791}}</ref><ref name=\"Moustafa\">{{cite journal | last1 = Moustafa | first1 = F | last2 = Feldman | first2 = SR | title = A Review of Phosphodiesterase-Inhibition and the Potential Role for Phosphodiesterase 4-Inhibitors in Clinical Dermatology | journal = Dermatology Online Journal | date = 16 May 2014 | volume = 20 | issue = 5 | pages = 22608 | pmid = 24852768 | url = http://escholarship.org/uc/item/2hx1m6kv.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"Spreitzer\">{{cite journal | last1 = Spreitzer | first1 = H | title = Neue Wirkstoffe: Crisaborol | journal = \u00d6sterreichische Apotheker-Zeitung | date = 16 August 2016 | issue = 17/2016 | language = German}}</ref> During preclinical and clinical development, crisaborole was called AN2728 and PF-06930164.<ref>{{cite web|title=Crisaborole|url=http://adisinsight.springer.com/drugs/800024239|publisher=AdisInsight|accessdate=24 July 2017|language=en}}</ref>\nThe drug was assumed to be potential $2bn-a-year blockbuster, when Pfizer acquired Anacor Pharmaceuticals. However, the drug was commercially not successful, reaching only 138 Mio $ sales in 2019 <ref>{{cite web|title=Pfizer Financial Report|url=https://s21.q4cdn.com/317678438/files/doc_financials/Quarterly/2019/q4/Q4-2019-PFE-Earnings-Release.pdf|publisher=Pfizer|accessdate=09 April 2020|language=en}} </ref>.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Tavaborole]] \u2013 a structurally related topical [[antifungal]] developed by Anacor\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Phosphodiesterase inhibitors}}\n\n[[Category:Ethers]]\n[[Category:Nitriles]]\n[[Category:Organoboron compounds]]\n[[Category:PDE4 inhibitors]]\n[[Category:Phosphodiesterase inhibitors]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Remove leading zero from dates", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crisaborole"}
{"title_page": "Muhammad Baqir al-Sadr", "text_new": "{{Details|Sadr (name)}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n|honorific-prefix = [[Grand Ayatollah]]\n| name=Muhammad Baqir al-Sadr\n| image=Mohammad Baqir al-Sadr.jpg\n| caption        =\n| religion = [[Islam]]\n| sect       = [[Usuli]] [[Twelver]] [[Shia Islam]]\n| location       = [[Najaf]], [[Iraq]]\n| Title          = [[Grand Ayatollah]]\n| ordination     =\n| post           = [[Grand Ayatollah]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1935|03|01}}\n| birth_place = [[Kadhimiya|al-Kazimiya]], [[Iraq]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1980|04|09|1935|03|01}}\n| death_place = [[Baghdad]], Iraq\n| resting_place  = [[Wadi-us-Salaam]], [[Najaf]]\n|nationality=Iraqi|citizenship=Iraq\n}}\n\n{{Twelvers}}\n\n'''Muhammad Baqir al-Sadr''' ({{lang-ar|\u0622\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0638\u0645\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u062f \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0627\u0642\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u062f\u0631}}, March 1, 1935&nbsp;\u2013 April 9, 1980), also known as '''al-Shah\u012bd al-Kh\u0101mis''', was an [[Iraq]]i [[Shia Islam|Shia]] cleric, philosopher, and the ideological founder of the [[Islamic Dawa Party]], born in [[Kadhimiya|al-Kadhimiya]], [[Iraq]]. He was father-in-law to [[Muqtada al-Sadr]], a cousin of [[Muhammad Sadeq al-Sadr]] and Imam [[Musa as-Sadr]]. His father [[Haydar al-Sadr]] was a well-respected high-ranking Shi'a cleric. His lineage can be traced back to [[Muhammad]] through the seventh Shia Imam [[Musa al-Kadhim|Musa al-Kazim]]. Muhammad Baqir Al-Sadr was executed in 1980 by the regime of [[Saddam Hussein]] along with his sister, Bintelhuda.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and education===\nMuhammad Baqir al-Sadr was born in [[Kadhimiya|al-Kazimiya]], [[Iraq]] to the prominent [[Sadr (name)|Sadr]] family, which originated from [[Jabal Amel]] in Lebanon. His father died in 1937, leaving the family destitute. In 1945, the family moved to the holy city of [[Najaf]], where al-Sadr would spend the rest of his life. He was a [[child prodigy]] who, at 10, was delivering lectures on [[Islamic history]]. At eleven, he was a student of [[logic]]. He wrote a book refuting materialistic [[philosophy]] when he was 24.<ref>Baqir Al-Sadr, ''Our Philosophy'', [[Taylor and Francis]], 1987, [https://books.google.com/books?id=vikOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PR13&dq=Musa+al+Sadr%2Bphilosophy&lr=&as_brr=3&as_pt=ALLTYPES&ei=TJviScT6DoKszgTToYSsDQ&hl=fr#PPR13,M1 p. xiii]</ref> Al-Sadr completed his religious studies at religious seminaries under [[al-Khoei]] and [[Muhsin al-Hakim]], and began teaching at the age of 25.\n\n===Later life ===\nAl-Sadr's works attracted the ire of the [[Baath Party]] leading to repeated imprisonment where he was often tortured. Despite this, he continued his work after being released.<ref name= 'A1'>{{cite news |last1=Al Asaad |first1=Sondoss |title=38 Years After Saddam's Heinous Execution of the Phenomenal Philosopher Ayatollah Al-Sadr and his Sister |url=https://moderndiplomacy.eu/2018/04/09/38-years-after-saddams-heinous-execution-of-the-phenomenal-philosopher-ayatollah-al-sadr-and-his-sister/ |accessdate=9 March 2019 |agency=Modern Diplomacy |publisher=moderndiplomacy.eu |date=9 April 2018}}</ref> When the Baathists arrested Ayatollah Al-Sadr in 1977, his sister [[Amina Sadr bint al-Huda]] made a speech in the Imam Ali mosque in Najaf inviting the people to demonstrate. Many demonstrations were held, forcing the Baathists to release Al-Sadr who was placed under house arrest.\n\nIn 1979\u20131980, [[1979\u201380 Shia uprising in Iraq|anti-Ba'ath riots]] arose in the Iraq's Shia areas by groups, who were working toward an Islamic revolution in their country.<ref name=efraimkarsh>{{cite book|title=The Iran\u2013Iraq War: 1980\u20131988|pages=1\u20138, 12\u201316, 19\u201382|author=Karsh, Efraim |publisher=Osprey Publishing |date=25 April 2002 |isbn=978-1841763712}}</ref> Saddam and his deputies believed that the riots had been inspired by the Iranian Revolution and instigated by Iran's government.<ref name=\"Farrokh 03\">{{cite book|last=Farrokh|first=Kaveh|title=Iran at War: 1500\u20131988|date=2011-12-20|publisher=Osprey Publishing|location=Oxford|isbn=978-1-78096-221-4}}</ref> In the aftermath of Iran's revolution, Iraq's Shia community called on Mohammad Baqir al-Sadr to be their \u201cIraqi Ayatollah Khomeini\u201d, leading a revolt against the Ba'ath regime.<ref name=brookings>{{Cite web | url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/order-from-chaos/2019/03/11/iraqs-failed-uprising-after-the-1979-iranian-revolution/ | title=Iraq's failed uprising after the 1979 Iranian revolution| date=2019-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Cockburn |first1=Patrick |title=Muqtada Al-Sadr and the Battle for the Future of Iraq |date=2008 |publisher=Simon and Schuster |isbn=978-1-4391-4119-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sbBH47BJfMsC&pg=PA27&dq=baqir+sadr+Iraq+Khomeini+revolution |accessdate=24 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Community leaders, tribal heads, and hundreds of ordinary members of the public paid their allegiance to al-Sadr.<ref name=brookings/> Protests then erupted in Baghdad and the predominantly Shia provinces of the south in May 1979.<ref name=brookings/> For nine days, protests against the regime unfolded, but were suppressed by the regime.<ref name=brookings/> The cleric's imprisonment led to another wave of protests in June after a seminal, powerful appeal from al-Sadr's sister, Bint al-Huda. Further clashes unfolded between the security forces and protestors. Najaf was put under siege and thousands were tortured and executed.<ref name=brookings/>\n\n===Execution===\nBaqir al-Sadr was finally arrested on 5 April 1980 with his sister, Sayedah Bent Al Huda.<ref name= 'A2'>{{cite news |last1=Al Asaad |first1=Sondoss |title=The ninth of April, the martyrdom of the Sadrs |url=https://www.tehrantimes.com/news/422510/The-ninth-of-April-the-martyrdom-of-the-Sadrs |accessdate=9 March 2019 |agency=[[Tehran Times]] |publisher=tehrantimes.com |date=10 April 2018}}</ref> They had formed a powerful militant movement in opposition to [[Saddam Hussein]]'s regime.<ref name ='A3'/>\n\nOn 9 April 1980, Al-Sadr and his sister were killed after being severely tortured by their Baathist captors.<ref name= 'A1'/> Signs of torture could be seen on the bodies.<ref name ='A3'>{{cite news |last1=Ramadani |first1=Sami |title=There's more to Sadr than meets the eye |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2004/aug/24/iraq.comment |accessdate=9 March 2019 |agency=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=theguardian.com |date=24 August 2004}}</ref><ref name='A4'>{{cite journal |last1=Aziz |first1=T.M |title=The Role of Muhammad Baqir al-Sadr in Shii Political Activism in Iraq from 1958 to 1980 |journal=[[International Journal of Middle East Studies]] |date=1 May 1993 |volume=25 |issue=2 |pages=207\u2013222 |jstor=164663 |doi=10.1017/S0020743800058499 }}</ref><ref name='A5'>{{cite news |last1=Marlowe |first1=Lara |title=Sectarianism laid bare |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/sectarianism-laid-bare-1.1191727 |accessdate=9 March 2019 |agency=[[The Irish Times]] |publisher=irishtimes.com |date=6 January 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe Baathists raped Bint Al Houda in front of her brother.<ref name='A5'/> An iron nail was hammered into Al-Sadr's head and he was then set on fire in Najaf.<ref name= 'A1'/><ref name= 'A2'/> It has been reported that Saddam himself killed them.<ref name ='A3'/> The Baathists delivered the bodies of Baqir Al-Sadr and Bint Al Huda to their cousin Sayyid Muhammad al-Sadr.<ref name ='A3'/>\n\nThey were buried in the [[Wadi-us-Salaam]] graveyard in the holy city of [[Najaf]] the same night.<ref name= 'A2'/> His execution raised no criticism from Western countries because Al-Sadr had openly supported Ayatollah [[Khomeini]] in Iran.<ref name='A4'/>\n\n==Scholarship==\nThe works by Baqir al-Sadr contains traditional Shia thoughts, while they also suggest the ways to though which Shia could \"accommodate modernity\". The two major works by him are ''[[Iqtisaduna]]'' on [[Islamic economics]], and ''[[Falsafatuna]]'' (Our Philosophy).<ref name=\"Nasr\">{{cite book |last1=Nasr |first1=Seyyed Husain |title=Expectation of the Millennium: Shi'ism in History |date=1989 |publisher=SUNY Press |isbn=978-0-88706-843-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=btmNZgztDrAC&pg=PA409&dq=Iqtisaduna+baqir+sadr |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> They were detailed critiques of [[Marxism]] that presented his early ideas on an alternative Islamic form of government. They were critiques of both [[socialism]] and [[capitalism]]. He was subsequently commissioned by the government of [[Kuwait]] to assess how that country's oil wealth could be managed in keeping with Islamic principles. This led to a major work on [[Islamic banking]], which still forms the basis for modern Islamic banks.<ref name=\"Behdad\">{{cite book |last1=Behdad |first1=Sohrab |last2=Nomani |first2=Farhad |title=Islam and the Everyday World: Public Policy Dilemmas |date=2006 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-134-20675-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zVdlj3xa-7AC&pg=PA211&lpg=PA211&dq=Islamic+banking+kuwait+oil+baqir+al+sadr |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nUsing his knowledge of the [[Quran]] and a subject-based approach to [[Quranic exegesis]], Al-Sadr extracted two concepts from the Holy text in relation to governance: ''khilafat al-insan'' (Man as heir or trustee of God) and ''shahadat al-anbiya'' (Prophets as witnesses). Al-Sadr explained that throughout history there have been \"...two lines. Man's line and the Prophet's line. The former is the ''khalifa'' (trustee) who inherits the earth from God; the latter is the ''shahid'' (witness)\".<ref name=\"Muhammed Baqir Al-Sadr 1979, p.132\">Muhammed Baqir Al-Sadr, ''Al-Islam yaqud al-hayat'', Qum, 1979, p.132</ref>\n\nAl-Sadr demonstrated that ''[[khilafa]]'' (governance) is \"a right given to the whole of humanity\" and defined it as an obligation given from God to the human race to \"tend the globe and administer human affairs\". This was a major advancement of Islamic political theory.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walberg |first1=Eric |title=From Postmodernism to Postsecularism: Re-emerging Islamic Civilization |date=2013 |publisher=SCB Distributors |isbn=978-0-9860362-4-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jYpXDwAAQBAJ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nWhile Al-Sadr identified ''khilafa'' as the obligation and right of the people, he used a broad-based explanation of a Quranic verse<ref>Quran 5:44</ref> to identify who held the responsibility of ''shahada'' in an Islamic state. First were the Prophets (anbiya'). Second were the Imams who are considered a divine (''rabbani'') continuation of the Prophets in this line. The last were the ''marja'iyya'' (''see [[Marja'|Marja]]'').<ref>Baqir Al-Sadr, ''Al-Islam yaqud al-hayat'', Qum, 1979, p.24</ref>\n\nWhile the two functions of ''khilafa'' and ''shahada'' (witness; supervision) were united during the times of the Prophets, they diverged during [[The Occultation|the occultation]] so that ''khilafa'' returned to the people (''umma'') and ''shahada'' to the scholars.<ref>Faleh A Jabar, The Shi'ite Movement in Iraq, London: Saqi Books, 2003, p.286</ref>\n\nAl-Sadr also presented a practical application of ''khilafa'', in the absence of the twelfth Imam. He argued that ''khilafa'' required the establishment of a democratic system whereby the people regularly elect their representatives in government:\n\n<blockquote>Islamic theory rejects monarchy as well as the various forms of dictatorial government; it also rejects the aristocratic regimes and proposes a form of government, which contains all the positive aspects of the democratic system.<ref>Muhammed Baqir Al-Sadr, Lamha fiqhiya, p.20</ref></blockquote>\nHe continued to champion this point until his final days:\n<blockquote>Lastly, I demand, in the name of all of you and in the name of the values you uphold, to allow the people the opportunity truly to exercise their right in running the affairs of the country by holding elections in which a council representing the ummah (people) could truly emerge.' ''<ref>Muhammed Baqir Al-Sadr, Principles of Islamic Jurisprudence, London: ICAS, 2003, p.15</ref></blockquote>\n\nAl-Sadr was executed by [[Saddam Hussein]] in 1980 before he was able to provide any details of the mechanism for the practical application of the ''shahada'' concept in an Islamic state. A few elaborations of ''shahada'' can be found in Al-Sadr's works. In his text ''Role of the Shiah Imams in the Reconstruction of Islamic Society'', Al-Sadr illustrates the scope and limitations of ''shahada'' by using the example of the third Shi'i Imam, [[Hussein ibn Ali]] (the grandson of the Prophet), who defied [[Yazid I|Yazid]], the ruler at the time. Al-Sadr explained that Yazid was not simply acting counter to Islamic teachings, as many rulers before and after him had done, but he was distorting the teachings and traditions of Islam and presenting his deviant ideas as representative of Islam itself. This, therefore, is what led Imam Hussein to intervene challenging Yazid in order to restore the true teachings of Islam, and consequently laying down his own life. In Al-Sadr's own words, the ''shahid's'' (witness \u2013 person performing ''shahada'' or supervision) duties are \"to protect the correct doctrines and to see that deviations do not grow to the extent of threatening the ideology itself\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hadad |first1=Sama |title=The Development of Shi\u2019ite Islamic Political Theory |date=2008 |pages=32\u201340 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/resrep03025.7 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=American Enterprise Institute}}</ref>\n\n==List of works==\nAl-Sadr engaged Western philosophical ideas, challenging them as necessary and incorporating them where appropriate, with the ultimate goal of demonstrating that religious knowledge was not antithetical to scientific knowledge.<ref name=\"TheMostLearned\">{{cite book|author=Walbridge, Linda S.|year=2001|title=The Most Learned of the Shi'a: The Institution of the Marja Taqlid|page=10|location=USA|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-513799-6}}</ref> The following is a list of his work:<ref>[http://www.imamreza.net/eng/imamreza.php?id=7241 The Super Genius Personality of Islam]</ref>\n\n===Jurisprudence===\n*''Buhuth fi Sharh al- 'Urwah al' Wuthqa'' (Discourses on the Commentary of ''al- 'Urwah al-Wuthqa''), four volumes\n*''Al-Ta'liqah 'ala Minhaj al-Salihin'' (Annotation of Ayatullah Hakim's ''Minhaj al-Salihin''), two volumes\n*''Al-Fatawa al-Wadhihah'' (Clear Decrees).\n*''Mujaz Ahkam al-Hajj'' (Summarized Rules of Hajj)\n*''Al-Ta'liqah 'ala Manasik al-Hajj'' (Annotation of Ayatullah Khui's Hajj Rites)\n*''Al-Ta'liqah 'ala Salah al-Jumu'ah'' (Annotation on Friday Prayer)\n\n===Fundamentals of the law===\n*''Durus fi Ilm al-Usul'' (Lessons in the Science of Jurisprudence), 3 Parts.<ref>This has been translated into English twice: by [[Roy Mottahedeh]] as ''Lessons in Islamic Jurisprudence'' (2005) {{ISBN|978-1-85168-393-2}} (Part 1 only) and anonymously as ''The Principles of Islamic Jurisprudence according to Shi'i Law'' (2003) {{ISBN|978-1-904063-12-4}}.</ref>\n*''Al-Ma'alim al-Jadidah lil-Usul'' (The New Signposts of Jurisprudence)\n*''Ghayat al-Fikr'' (The Highest Degree of Thought)\n\n===Philosophy===\n*''[[Falsafatuna]]'' ([https://www.al-islam.org/our-philosophy-falsafatuna-ayatullah-sayyid-muhammad-baqir-sadr]) (Our Philosophy) published in 1959\n\n===Logic===\n*''Al-Usus al-Mantiqiyyah lil-Istiqra{{'}}'' (Logical Foundations of Induction)\n\n===Theology===\n*''Al-Mujaz fi Usul al-Din: al-Mursil, al-Rasul, al-Risalah'' (The Summarized Principles of Religion: The Sender, The Messenger, The Message)\n*''Al-Tashayyu' wa al-Islam - Bahth Hawl al-Wilayah'' (Discourse on Divine Authority)\n*''Bahth Hawl al-Mahdi'' (Discourse on Imam Mahdi)\n\n===Economics===\n*[[Iqtisaduna]] (Our Economy)\n*''Al-Bank al-la Ribawi fi al-Islam'' (Usury-free Banking in Islam)\n*''Maqalat Iqtisadiyyah'' (Essays in Economy)\n\n===Qur'anic commentaries===\n*''Al-Tafair al-Mawzu'i lil-Qur'an al-Karim - al-Madrasah al-Qur'aniyyah'' (The Thematic Exegesis of the Holy Qur'an)\n*''1Buhuth fi 'Ulum al-Qur'an'' (Discourses on Qur'anic Sciences)\n*''Maqalat Qur'aniyyah'' (Essays on Qur'an)\n\n===History===\n*''Ahl al-Bayt Tanawwu' Ahdaf wa Wahdah Hadaf'' (Ahl al- Bayt, Variety of Objectives Towards a Single Goal)\n*''Fadak fi al-Tarikh'' (Fadak in History)\n\n===Islamic culture===\n*''Al-Islam Yaqud al-Hayah'' (Islam Directive to Life)\n*''Al-Madrasah al-Islamiyyah'' (Islamic School)\n*''Risalatuna'' (Our Mission)\n*''Nazrah Ammah fi al-Ibadat'' (General View on Rites of Worship)\n*''Maqalat wa Muhazrat'' (Essays and Lectures)\n\n===Articles===\n*\"Al-'Amal wa al-Ahdaf\" (The Deeds and the Goals): Min Fikr al- Da'wah. No. 13. Islamic Da'wah Party, central propagation, place and date of publication unknown.\n*\"Al-'Amal al-Salih fi al-Quran\" (The Proper Deeds According to Qur'an): Ikhtrna Lak. Beirut: Dar al-Zahra', 1982\n*\"Ahl al-Bayt: Tanawu' Adwar wa-Wihdat Hadaf\" (The Household of the Prophet: Diversity of Roles But Unified Goal). Beirut: Dar al-Ta'ruf, 1985.\n*\"Bahth Hawla al-Mahdi\" (Thesis on Messiah). Beirut: Dar al- Ta'ruf, 1983.\n*\"Bahth Hawla al-Wilayah\" (Thesis on Rulership). Kuwait: Dar al- Tawhid, 1977.\n*\"Da'watana il al-Islam Yajeb an Takun Enqilabiyah,\" (Our Call for Islam Must be Revolutionary): Fikr al-Da'wah, No. 13. Islamic Da'wah Party, central propagation, place and date of publication unknown.\n*\"Dawr al-A'imah fi al-Hayat al-Islamiyah\" (The Role of Imams in Muslims' Life): Ikhtarna Lak. Beirut: Dar al-Zahra', 1982\n*\"al-Dawlah al-Islamiyah\" (The Islamic State), al-Jihad (14 March 1983): 5\n*\"Hawla al-Marhala al-Ula min 'Amal al-Da'wah\" (On the First Stage of Da'wah Political Program): Min Fikr al-Da'wah. No. 13. Islamic Da'wah Party, central propagation, place and date of publishing unknown.\n*\"Hawla al-Ism wa-al-Shakl al-Tanzimi li-Hizb al-Da'wah al- Islamiyah\" (On the Name and the Structural Organization of the Islamic Da'wah Party): Min Fikr al-Da'wah. No. 13. Islamic Da'wah Party, central propagation, place and date of publication unknown.\n*\"al-Huriyah fi al-Quran\" (Freedom According to the Quran): Ikhtarna Lak. Beirut: Dar al-Zahra', 1982\n*\"al-Itijahat al-Mustaqbaliyah li-Harakat al-Ijtihad\" (The Future Trends of the Process of Ijtihad): Ikhtarna Lak. Beirut: Dar al-Zahra', 1980.\n*\"al-Insan al-Mu'asir wa-al-Mushkilah al-Ijtima'yah\" (Contemporary Man and the Social Problem)\n*\"al-Janib al-Iqtisadi Min al-Nizam al-Islami\" (The Economic Perspective of the Islamic System): Ikhtarna Lak. Beirut: Dar al-Zahra', 1982\n*\"Khalafat al-Insan wa-Shahadat al-Anbia{{'}}\" (Victory Role of Man, and Witness Role of Prophets): al-Islam Yaqwod al-Hayat. Iran: Islamic Ministry of Guidance, n.d.\n*\"Khatut Tafsiliyah 'An Iqtisad al-Mujtama' al-Islami (General Basis of Economics of Islamic Society): al-Islam Yaqud al-Hayah. Iran: Islamic Ministry of Guidance, n.d.\n*\"Lamha fiqhiyah Hawla Dustur al-Jumhuriyah al-Islamiyah\" (A Preliminary Jurisprudence Basis of the Constitution of the Islamic Republic): al-Islam Yaqwod al-Hayat Iran: Islamic Ministry of Guidance, n.d.\n*\"Madha Ta'ruf 'an al-Iqtisad al-Islami\" (What Do You Know About Islamic Economics). al-Islam Yaqwod al-Hayat Iran: Islamic Ministry of Guidance, n.d.\n*\"Manabi' al-Qudra fi al-Dawlah al-Islamiyah\" (The Sources of Power in an Islamic State). al-Islam Yaqwod al-Hayat Iran: Islamic Ministry of Guidance, n.d.\n*\"al-Mihna\" (The Ordeal). Sawt al-Wihdah, Nos. 5, 6, 7. (n.d)\n*\"Minhaj al-Salihin\" (The Path of the Righteous). Beirut: Dar al- Ta'aruf, 1980.\n*\"Muqaddimat fi al-Tafsir al-Mawdu'i Lil-Quran\" (Introductions in Thematic Exegesis of the Quran). Kuwait: Dar al- Tawjyyh al-Islami, 1980.\n*\"Nazarah 'Amah fi al-'Ibadat\" (General Outlook on Worship): al-Fatawa al-Wadhiha. Beirut: Dar al-Ta'aruf, 1981.\n*\"al-Nazriyah al-Islamiyah li-Tawzi' al-Masadr al-Tabi'iyah\" (Islamic Theory of Distribution of Natural Resources): Ikhtarna Lak. Beirut: Dar al-Zahra', 1982.\n*\"al-Nizam al-Islami Muqaranan bil-Nizam al-Ra'smali wa-al- Markisi\" (The Islamic System Compared with The Capitalist and The Marxist Systems). Ikhtarna Lak. Beirut: Dar-al Zahra', 1982.\n*\"Risalatuna wa-al-Da'wah\" (Our Message and Our Sermon). Risalatuna. Beirut: al-Dar al-Islamiyah, 1981.\n*\"Al-Shakhsiyah al-Islamiyah\" (Muslim Personality): Min Fikr al-Da'wah al-Islamiyah (Of the Thoughts of Islamic Da'wah). No. 13. Islamic Da'wah Party, central propagation, place and date of publication unknown.\n*\"Surah 'An Iqtisad al-Mujtama' al-Islami\" (A Perspective on the Economy of Muslim Society). al-Islam Yaqwod al-Hayat Iran: Islamic Ministry of Guidance, n.d.\n*\"al-Usus al-Amah li-al-Bank fi al-Mujtam al-Islami\" (The General Basis of Banks in Islamic Society). in al-Islam Yaqwod al-Hayat Iran: Islamic Ministry of Guidance, n.d.\n*\"Utruhat al-Marja'iyah al-Salihah\" (Thesis on Suitable ''Marja'iyah''). In Kazim al-Ha'iri, Mabahith fi 'Ilm al-Usul.Qum, Iran: n.p., 1988.\n*\"al-Yaqin al-Riyadi wa-al-Mantiq al-Waz'i\" (The Mathematic Certainty and the Phenomenal Logic): Ikhtrna Lak. Beirut: Dar al-Zahra', 1982.\n*\"Preface to al-Sahifah al-Sajadiyah\" (of Imam Ali ibn Hussein al-Sajad) Tehran: al-Maktabah al-Islamiyah al-Kubra, n.d.\n\n==Notable colleagues and students==\n* [[Hassan Nasrallah]]\n* [[Muhammad Hussein Fadlullah]]\n* [[Muhammad Baqir al-Hakim]] (Late)\n* [[Muhammad Muhammad Sadiq as-Sadr]]\n* [[Mohsen Araki]]\n* [[Kazem al-Haeri]]\n* [[Abbas al-Musawi]]\n* [[Talib Jauhari]]\n* [[Syed Sajid Ali Naqvi]]\n* [[Ali El-Amine]]\n* [[Allama Syed Zeeshan Haider Jawadi]]\n\n==Books==\n* ''[[Iqtisaduna]]''\n* ''[[Falsafatuna]]''\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Five Martyrs of Shia Islam]]\n*[[Shahid Awwal]]\n*[[Shahid Khamis]]\n*[[Shahid Rabay]]\n*[[Shahid Salis]]\n*[[Shahid Thani]]\n*[[Muhammad al-Tijani]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Mallat, Chibli. \"Muhammad Baqir as-Sadr.\" ''Pioneers of Islamic Revival.'' ed. Ali Rahnema. London: Zed Books, 1994\n\n{{Islamic theology}}\n{{Islamic philosophy}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sadr, Muhammad Baqir Al-}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:Iraqi Shia clerics]]\n[[Category:Iraqi people of Lebanese descent]]\n[[Category:Islamic philosophers]]\n[[Category:Iraqi ayatollahs]]\n[[Category:People from Kadhimiya]]\n[[Category:Iraqi Shia Muslims]]\n[[Category:Al-Moussawi family]]\n[[Category:Islamic Dawa Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Shia Muslim scholars]]\n[[Category:Executed philosophers]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions by Iraq]]\n[[Category:Twelvers]]\n[[Category:Iraqi dissidents]]\n", "text_old": "{{Details|Sadr (name)}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n|honorific-prefix = [[Grand Ayatollah]]\n| name=Muhammad Baqir al-Sadr\n| image=Mohammad Baqir al-Sadr.jpg\n| caption        =\n| religion = [[Islam]]\n| sect       = [[Usuli]] [[Twelver]] [[Shia Islam]]\n| location       = [[Najaf]], [[Iraq]]\n| Title          = [[Grand Ayatollah]]\n| ordination     =\n| post           = [[Grand Ayatollah]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1935|03|01}}\n| birth_place = [[Kadhimiya|al-Kazimiya]], [[Iraq]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1980|04|09|1935|03|01}}\n| death_place = [[Baghdad]], Iraq\n| resting_place  = [[Wadi-us-Salaam]], [[Najaf]]\n|nationality=Iraqi|citizenship=Iraq\n}}\n\n{{Twelvers}}\n\n'''Muhammad Baqir al-Sadr''' ({{lang-ar|\u0622\u064a\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647 \u0627\u0644\u0639\u0638\u0645\u0649 \u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u062f \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0627\u0642\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u062f\u0631}}) (March 1, 1935 \u2013 April 9, 1980), also known as '''al-Shah\u012bd al-Kh\u0101mis''', was an [[Iraq]]i [[Shia Islam|Shia]] cleric, philosopher, and the ideological founder of the [[Islamic Dawa Party]], born in [[Kadhimiya|al-Kadhimiya]], [[Iraq]]. He was father-in-law to [[Muqtada al-Sadr]], a cousin of [[Muhammad Sadeq al-Sadr]] and Imam [[Musa as-Sadr]]. His father [[Haydar al-Sadr]] was a well-respected high-ranking Shi'a cleric. His lineage can be traced back to [[Muhammad]] through the seventh Shia Imam [[Musa al-Kadhim|Musa al-Kazim]]. Muhammad Baqir Al-Sadr was executed in 1980 by the regime of [[Saddam Hussein]] along with his sister, Bintelhuda.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and education===\nMuhammad Baqir al-Sadr was born in [[Kadhimiya|al-Kazimiya]], [[Iraq]] to the prominent [[Sadr (name)|Sadr]] family, which originated from [[Jabal Amel]] in Lebanon. His father died in 1937, leaving the family destitute. In 1945, the family moved to the holy city of [[Najaf]], where al-Sadr would spend the rest of his life. He was a [[child prodigy]] who, at 10, was delivering lectures on [[Islamic history]]. At eleven, he was a student of [[logic]]. He wrote a book refuting materialistic [[philosophy]] when he was 24.<ref>Baqir Al-Sadr, ''Our Philosophy'', [[Taylor and Francis]], 1987, [https://books.google.com/books?id=vikOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PR13&dq=Musa+al+Sadr%2Bphilosophy&lr=&as_brr=3&as_pt=ALLTYPES&ei=TJviScT6DoKszgTToYSsDQ&hl=fr#PPR13,M1 p. xiii]</ref> Al-Sadr completed his religious studies at religious seminaries under [[al-Khoei]] and [[Muhsin al-Hakim]], and began teaching at the age of 25.\n\n===Later life ===\nAl-Sadr's works attracted the ire of the [[Baath Party]] leading to repeated imprisonment where he was often tortured. Despite this, he continued his work after being released.<ref name= 'A1'>{{cite news |last1=Al Asaad |first1=Sondoss |title=38 Years After Saddam's Heinous Execution of the Phenomenal Philosopher Ayatollah Al-Sadr and his Sister |url=https://moderndiplomacy.eu/2018/04/09/38-years-after-saddams-heinous-execution-of-the-phenomenal-philosopher-ayatollah-al-sadr-and-his-sister/ |accessdate=9 March 2019 |agency=Modern Diplomacy |publisher=moderndiplomacy.eu |date=9 April 2018}}</ref> When the Baathists arrested Ayatollah Al-Sadr in 1977, his sister [[Amina Sadr bint al-Huda]] made a speech in the Imam Ali mosque in Najaf inviting the people to demonstrate. Many demonstrations were held, forcing the Baathists to release Al-Sadr who was placed under house arrest.\n\nIn 1979\u20131980, [[1979\u201380 Shia uprising in Iraq|anti-Ba'ath riots]] arose in the Iraq's Shia areas by groups, who were working toward an Islamic revolution in their country.<ref name=efraimkarsh>{{cite book|title=The Iran\u2013Iraq War: 1980\u20131988|pages=1\u20138, 12\u201316, 19\u201382|author=Karsh, Efraim |publisher=Osprey Publishing |date=25 April 2002 |isbn=978-1841763712}}</ref> Saddam and his deputies believed that the riots had been inspired by the Iranian Revolution and instigated by Iran's government.<ref name=\"Farrokh 03\">{{cite book|last=Farrokh|first=Kaveh|title=Iran at War: 1500\u20131988|date=2011-12-20|publisher=Osprey Publishing|location=Oxford|isbn=978-1-78096-221-4}}</ref> In the aftermath of Iran's revolution, Iraq's Shia community called on Mohammad Baqir al-Sadr to be their \u201cIraqi Ayatollah Khomeini\u201d, leading a revolt against the Ba'ath regime.<ref name=brookings>{{Cite web | url=https://www.brookings.edu/blog/order-from-chaos/2019/03/11/iraqs-failed-uprising-after-the-1979-iranian-revolution/ | title=Iraq's failed uprising after the 1979 Iranian revolution| date=2019-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Cockburn |first1=Patrick |title=Muqtada Al-Sadr and the Battle for the Future of Iraq |date=2008 |publisher=Simon and Schuster |isbn=978-1-4391-4119-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sbBH47BJfMsC&pg=PA27&dq=baqir+sadr+Iraq+Khomeini+revolution |accessdate=24 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Community leaders, tribal heads, and hundreds of ordinary members of the public paid their allegiance to al-Sadr.<ref name=brookings/> Protests then erupted in Baghdad and the predominantly Shia provinces of the south in May 1979.<ref name=brookings/> For nine days, protests against the regime unfolded, but were suppressed by the regime.<ref name=brookings/> The cleric's imprisonment led to another wave of protests in June after a seminal, powerful appeal from al-Sadr's sister, Bint al-Huda. Further clashes unfolded between the security forces and protestors. Najaf was put under siege and thousands were tortured and executed.<ref name=brookings/>\n\n===Execution===\nBaqir al-Sadr was finally arrested on 5 April 1980 with his sister, Sayedah Bent Al Huda.<ref name= 'A2'>{{cite news |last1=Al Asaad |first1=Sondoss |title=The ninth of April, the martyrdom of the Sadrs |url=https://www.tehrantimes.com/news/422510/The-ninth-of-April-the-martyrdom-of-the-Sadrs |accessdate=9 March 2019 |agency=[[Tehran Times]] |publisher=tehrantimes.com |date=10 April 2018}}</ref> They had formed a powerful militant movement in opposition to [[Saddam Hussein]]'s regime.<ref name ='A3'/>\n\nOn 9 April 1980, Al-Sadr and his sister were killed after being severely tortured by their Baathist captors.<ref name= 'A1'/> Signs of torture could be seen on the bodies.<ref name ='A3'>{{cite news |last1=Ramadani |first1=Sami |title=There's more to Sadr than meets the eye |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2004/aug/24/iraq.comment |accessdate=9 March 2019 |agency=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=theguardian.com |date=24 August 2004}}</ref><ref name='A4'>{{cite journal |last1=Aziz |first1=T.M |title=The Role of Muhammad Baqir al-Sadr in Shii Political Activism in Iraq from 1958 to 1980 |journal=[[International Journal of Middle East Studies]] |date=1 May 1993 |volume=25 |issue=2 |pages=207\u2013222 |jstor=164663 |doi=10.1017/S0020743800058499 }}</ref><ref name='A5'>{{cite news |last1=Marlowe |first1=Lara |title=Sectarianism laid bare |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/sectarianism-laid-bare-1.1191727 |accessdate=9 March 2019 |agency=[[The Irish Times]] |publisher=irishtimes.com |date=6 January 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe Baathists raped Bint Al Houda in front of her brother.<ref name='A5'/> An iron nail was hammered into Al-Sadr's head and he was then set on fire in Najaf.<ref name= 'A1'/><ref name= 'A2'/> It has been reported that Saddam himself killed them.<ref name ='A3'/> The Baathists delivered the bodies of Baqir Al-Sadr and Bint Al Huda to their cousin Sayyid Muhammad al-Sadr.<ref name ='A3'/>\n\nThey were buried in the [[Wadi-us-Salaam]] graveyard in the holy city of [[Najaf]] the same night.<ref name= 'A2'/> His execution raised no criticism from Western countries because Al-Sadr had openly supported Ayatollah [[Khomeini]] in Iran.<ref name='A4'/>\n\n==Scholarship==\nThe works by Baqir al-Sadr contains traditional Shia thoughts, while they also suggest the ways to though which Shia could \"accommodate modernity\". The two major works by him are ''[[Iqtisaduna]]'' on [[Islamic economics]], and ''[[Falsafatuna]]'' (Our Philosophy).<ref name=\"Nasr\">{{cite book |last1=Nasr |first1=Seyyed Husain |title=Expectation of the Millennium: Shi'ism in History |date=1989 |publisher=SUNY Press |isbn=978-0-88706-843-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=btmNZgztDrAC&pg=PA409&dq=Iqtisaduna+baqir+sadr |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> They were detailed critiques of [[Marxism]] that presented his early ideas on an alternative Islamic form of government. They were critiques of both [[socialism]] and [[capitalism]]. He was subsequently commissioned by the government of [[Kuwait]] to assess how that country's oil wealth could be managed in keeping with Islamic principles. This led to a major work on [[Islamic banking]], which still forms the basis for modern Islamic banks.<ref name=\"Behdad\">{{cite book |last1=Behdad |first1=Sohrab |last2=Nomani |first2=Farhad |title=Islam and the Everyday World: Public Policy Dilemmas |date=2006 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-134-20675-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zVdlj3xa-7AC&pg=PA211&lpg=PA211&dq=Islamic+banking+kuwait+oil+baqir+al+sadr |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nUsing his knowledge of the [[Quran]] and a subject-based approach to [[Quranic exegesis]], Al-Sadr extracted two concepts from the Holy text in relation to governance: ''khilafat al-insan'' (Man as heir or trustee of God) and ''shahadat al-anbiya'' (Prophets as witnesses). Al-Sadr explained that throughout history there have been \"...two lines.  Man's line and the Prophet's line.  The former is the ''khalifa'' (trustee) who inherits the earth from God; the latter is the ''shahid'' (witness)\".<ref name=\"Muhammed Baqir Al-Sadr 1979, p.132\">Muhammed Baqir Al-Sadr, ''Al-Islam yaqud al-hayat'', Qum, 1979, p.132</ref>\n\nAl-Sadr demonstrated that ''[[khilafa]]'' (governance) is \"a right given to the whole of humanity\" and defined it as an obligation given from God to the human race to \"tend the globe and administer human affairs\".  This was a major advancement of Islamic political theory.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Walberg |first1=Eric |title=From Postmodernism to Postsecularism: Re-emerging Islamic Civilization |date=2013 |publisher=SCB Distributors |isbn=978-0-9860362-4-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jYpXDwAAQBAJ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nWhile Al-Sadr identified ''khilafa'' as the obligation and right of the people, he used a broad-based explanation of a Quranic verse<ref>Quran 5:44</ref> to identify who held the responsibility of ''shahada'' in an Islamic state. First were the Prophets (anbiya'). Second were the Imams who are considered a divine (''rabbani'') continuation of the Prophets in this line. The last were the ''marja'iyya'' (''see [[Marja'|Marja]]'').<ref>Baqir Al-Sadr, ''Al-Islam yaqud al-hayat'', Qum, 1979, p.24</ref>\n\nWhile the two functions of ''khilafa'' and ''shahada'' (witness; supervision) were united during the times of the Prophets, they diverged during [[The Occultation|the occultation]] so that ''khilafa'' returned to the people (''umma'') and ''shahada'' to the scholars.<ref>Faleh A Jabar, The Shi'ite Movement in Iraq, London: Saqi Books, 2003, p.286</ref>\n\nAl-Sadr also presented a practical application of ''khilafa'', in the absence of the twelfth Imam.  He argued that ''khilafa'' required the establishment of a democratic system whereby the people regularly elect their representatives in government:\n\n<blockquote>Islamic theory rejects monarchy as well as the various forms of dictatorial government; it also rejects the aristocratic regimes and proposes a form of government, which contains all the positive aspects of the democratic system.<ref>Muhammed Baqir Al-Sadr, Lamha fiqhiya, p.20</ref></blockquote>\nHe continued to champion this point until his final days:\n<blockquote>Lastly, I demand, in the name of all of you and in the name of the values you uphold, to allow the people the opportunity truly to exercise their right in running the affairs of the country by holding elections in which a council representing the ummah (people) could truly emerge.' ''<ref>Muhammed Baqir Al-Sadr, Principles of Islamic Jurisprudence, London: ICAS, 2003, p.15</ref></blockquote>\n\nAl-Sadr was executed by [[Saddam Hussein]] in 1980 before he was able to provide any details of the mechanism for the practical application of the ''shahada''  concept in an Islamic state. A few elaborations of ''shahada'' can be found in Al-Sadr's works. In his text ''Role of the Shiah Imams in the Reconstruction of Islamic Society'', Al-Sadr illustrates the scope and limitations of ''shahada'' by using the example of the third Shi'i Imam, [[Hussein ibn Ali]] (the grandson of the Prophet), who defied [[Yazid I|Yazid]], the ruler at the time. Al-Sadr explained that Yazid was not simply acting counter to Islamic teachings, as many rulers before and after him had done, but he was distorting the teachings and traditions of Islam and presenting his deviant ideas as representative of Islam itself. This, therefore, is what led Imam Hussein to intervene challenging Yazid in order to restore the true teachings of Islam, and consequently laying down his own life. In Al-Sadr's own words, the ''shahid's'' (witness \u2013 person performing ''shahada'' or supervision) duties are \"to protect the correct doctrines and to see that deviations do not grow to the extent of threatening the ideology itself\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hadad |first1=Sama |title=The Development of Shi\u2019ite Islamic Political Theory |date=2008 |pages=32\u201340 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/resrep03025.7 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |publisher=American Enterprise Institute}}</ref>\n\n==List of works==\nAl-Sadr engaged Western philosophical ideas, challenging them as necessary and incorporating them where appropriate, with the ultimate goal of demonstrating that religious knowledge was not antithetical to scientific knowledge.<ref name=\"TheMostLearned\">{{cite book|author=Walbridge, Linda S.|year=2001|title=The Most Learned of the Shi'a: The Institution of the Marja Taqlid|page=10|location=USA|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-513799-6}}</ref> The following is a list of his work:<ref>[http://www.imamreza.net/eng/imamreza.php?id=7241 The Super Genius Personality of Islam]</ref>\n\n===Jurisprudence===\n*''Buhuth fi Sharh al- 'Urwah al' Wuthqa'' (Discourses on the Commentary of ''al- 'Urwah al-Wuthqa''), four volumes\n*''Al-Ta'liqah 'ala Minhaj al-Salihin'' (Annotation of Ayatullah Hakim's ''Minhaj al-Salihin''), two volumes\n*''Al-Fatawa al-Wadhihah'' (Clear Decrees).\n*''Mujaz Ahkam al-Hajj'' (Summarized Rules of Hajj)\n*''Al-Ta'liqah 'ala Manasik al-Hajj'' (Annotation of Ayatullah Khui's Hajj Rites)\n*''Al-Ta'liqah 'ala Salah al-Jumu'ah'' (Annotation on Friday Prayer)\n\n===Fundamentals of the law===\n*''Durus fi Ilm al-Usul'' (Lessons in the Science of Jurisprudence), 3 Parts.<ref>This has been translated into English twice: by [[Roy Mottahedeh]] as ''Lessons in Islamic Jurisprudence'' (2005) {{ISBN|978-1-85168-393-2}} (Part 1 only) and anonymously as ''The Principles of Islamic Jurisprudence according to Shi'i Law'' (2003) {{ISBN|978-1-904063-12-4}}.</ref>\n*''Al-Ma'alim al-Jadidah lil-Usul'' (The New Signposts of Jurisprudence)\n*''Ghayat al-Fikr'' (The Highest Degree of Thought)\n\n===Philosophy===\n*''[[Falsafatuna]]'' ([https://www.al-islam.org/our-philosophy-falsafatuna-ayatullah-sayyid-muhammad-baqir-sadr]) (Our Philosophy) published in 1959\n\n===Logic===\n*''Al-Usus al-Mantiqiyyah lil-Istiqra{{'}}'' (Logical Foundations of Induction)\n\n===Theology===\n*''Al-Mujaz fi Usul al-Din: al-Mursil, al-Rasul, al-Risalah'' (The Summarized Principles of Religion: The Sender, The Messenger, The Message)\n*''Al-Tashayyu' wa al-Islam - Bahth Hawl al-Wilayah'' (Discourse on Divine Authority)\n*''Bahth Hawl al-Mahdi'' (Discourse on Imam Mahdi)\n\n===Economics===\n*[[Iqtisaduna]] (Our Economy)\n*''Al-Bank al-la Ribawi fi al-Islam'' (Usury-free Banking in Islam)\n*''Maqalat Iqtisadiyyah'' (Essays in Economy)\n\n===Qur'anic commentaries===\n*''Al-Tafair al-Mawzu'i lil-Qur'an al-Karim - al-Madrasah al-Qur'aniyyah'' (The Thematic Exegesis of the Holy Qur'an)\n*''1Buhuth fi 'Ulum al-Qur'an'' (Discourses on Qur'anic Sciences)\n*''Maqalat Qur'aniyyah'' (Essays on Qur'an)\n\n===History===\n*''Ahl al-Bayt Tanawwu' Ahdaf wa Wahdah Hadaf'' (Ahl al- Bayt, Variety of Objectives Towards a Single Goal)\n*''Fadak fi al-Tarikh'' (Fadak in History)\n\n===Islamic culture===\n*''Al-Islam Yaqud al-Hayah'' (Islam Directive to Life)\n*''Al-Madrasah al-Islamiyyah'' (Islamic School)\n*''Risalatuna'' (Our Mission)\n*''Nazrah Ammah fi al-Ibadat'' (General View on Rites of Worship)\n*''Maqalat wa Muhazrat'' (Essays and Lectures)\n\n===Articles===\n*\"Al-'Amal wa al-Ahdaf\" (The Deeds and the Goals): Min Fikr al- Da'wah. No. 13. Islamic Da'wah Party, central propagation, place and date of publication unknown.\n*\"Al-'Amal al-Salih fi al-Quran\" (The Proper Deeds According to Qur'an): Ikhtrna Lak. Beirut: Dar al-Zahra', 1982\n*\"Ahl al-Bayt: Tanawu' Adwar wa-Wihdat Hadaf\" (The Household of the Prophet: Diversity of Roles But Unified Goal). Beirut: Dar al-Ta'ruf, 1985.\n*\"Bahth Hawla al-Mahdi\" (Thesis on Messiah). Beirut: Dar al- Ta'ruf, 1983.\n*\"Bahth Hawla al-Wilayah\" (Thesis on Rulership). Kuwait: Dar al- Tawhid, 1977.\n*\"Da'watana il al-Islam Yajeb an Takun Enqilabiyah,\" (Our Call for Islam Must be Revolutionary): Fikr al-Da'wah, No. 13. Islamic Da'wah Party, central propagation, place and date of publication unknown.\n*\"Dawr al-A'imah fi al-Hayat al-Islamiyah\" (The Role of Imams in Muslims' Life): Ikhtarna Lak. Beirut: Dar al-Zahra', 1982\n*\"al-Dawlah al-Islamiyah\" (The Islamic State), al-Jihad (14 March 1983): 5\n*\"Hawla al-Marhala al-Ula min 'Amal al-Da'wah\" (On the First Stage of Da'wah Political Program): Min Fikr al-Da'wah. No. 13. Islamic Da'wah Party, central propagation, place and date of publishing unknown.\n*\"Hawla al-Ism wa-al-Shakl al-Tanzimi li-Hizb al-Da'wah al- Islamiyah\" (On the Name and the Structural Organization of the Islamic Da'wah Party): Min Fikr al-Da'wah. No. 13. Islamic Da'wah Party, central propagation, place and date of publication unknown.\n*\"al-Huriyah fi al-Quran\" (Freedom According to the Quran): Ikhtarna Lak. Beirut: Dar al-Zahra', 1982\n*\"al-Itijahat al-Mustaqbaliyah li-Harakat al-Ijtihad\" (The Future Trends of the Process of Ijtihad): Ikhtarna Lak. Beirut: Dar al-Zahra', 1980.\n*\"al-Insan al-Mu'asir wa-al-Mushkilah al-Ijtima'yah\" (Contemporary Man and the Social Problem)\n*\"al-Janib al-Iqtisadi Min al-Nizam al-Islami\" (The Economic Perspective of the Islamic System): Ikhtarna Lak. Beirut: Dar al-Zahra', 1982\n*\"Khalafat al-Insan wa-Shahadat al-Anbia{{'}}\" (Victory Role of Man, and Witness Role of Prophets): al-Islam Yaqwod al-Hayat. Iran: Islamic Ministry of Guidance, n.d.\n*\"Khatut Tafsiliyah 'An Iqtisad al-Mujtama' al-Islami (General Basis of Economics of Islamic Society): al-Islam Yaqud al-Hayah. Iran: Islamic Ministry of Guidance, n.d.\n*\"Lamha fiqhiyah Hawla Dustur al-Jumhuriyah al-Islamiyah\" (A Preliminary Jurisprudence Basis of the Constitution of the Islamic Republic): al-Islam Yaqwod al-Hayat Iran: Islamic Ministry of Guidance, n.d.\n*\"Madha Ta'ruf 'an al-Iqtisad al-Islami\" (What Do You Know About Islamic Economics). al-Islam Yaqwod al-Hayat Iran: Islamic Ministry of Guidance, n.d.\n*\"Manabi' al-Qudra fi al-Dawlah al-Islamiyah\" (The Sources of Power in an Islamic State). al-Islam Yaqwod al-Hayat Iran: Islamic Ministry of Guidance, n.d.\n*\"al-Mihna\" (The Ordeal). Sawt al-Wihdah, Nos. 5, 6, 7. (n.d)\n*\"Minhaj al-Salihin\" (The Path of the Righteous). Beirut: Dar al- Ta'aruf, 1980.\n*\"Muqaddimat fi al-Tafsir al-Mawdu'i Lil-Quran\" (Introductions in Thematic Exegesis of the Quran). Kuwait: Dar al- Tawjyyh al-Islami, 1980.\n*\"Nazarah 'Amah fi al-'Ibadat\" (General Outlook on Worship): al-Fatawa al-Wadhiha. Beirut: Dar al-Ta'aruf, 1981.\n*\"al-Nazriyah al-Islamiyah li-Tawzi' al-Masadr al-Tabi'iyah\" (Islamic Theory of Distribution of Natural Resources): Ikhtarna Lak. Beirut: Dar al-Zahra', 1982.\n*\"al-Nizam al-Islami Muqaranan bil-Nizam al-Ra'smali wa-al- Markisi\" (The Islamic System Compared with The Capitalist and The Marxist Systems). Ikhtarna Lak. Beirut: Dar-al Zahra', 1982.\n*\"Risalatuna wa-al-Da'wah\" (Our Message and Our Sermon). Risalatuna. Beirut: al-Dar al-Islamiyah, 1981.\n*\"Al-Shakhsiyah al-Islamiyah\" (Muslim Personality): Min Fikr al-Da'wah al-Islamiyah (Of the Thoughts of Islamic Da'wah). No. 13. Islamic Da'wah Party, central propagation, place and date of publication unknown.\n*\"Surah 'An Iqtisad al-Mujtama' al-Islami\" (A Perspective on the Economy of Muslim Society). al-Islam Yaqwod al-Hayat Iran: Islamic Ministry of Guidance, n.d.\n*\"al-Usus al-Amah li-al-Bank fi al-Mujtam al-Islami\" (The General Basis of Banks in Islamic Society). in al-Islam Yaqwod al-Hayat Iran: Islamic Ministry of Guidance, n.d.\n*\"Utruhat al-Marja'iyah al-Salihah\" (Thesis on Suitable ''Marja'iyah''). In Kazim al-Ha'iri, Mabahith fi 'Ilm al-Usul.Qum, Iran: n.p., 1988.\n*\"al-Yaqin al-Riyadi wa-al-Mantiq al-Waz'i\" (The Mathematic Certainty and the Phenomenal Logic): Ikhtrna Lak. Beirut: Dar al-Zahra', 1982.\n*\"Preface to al-Sahifah al-Sajadiyah\" (of Imam Ali ibn Hussein al-Sajad) Tehran: al-Maktabah al-Islamiyah al-Kubra, n.d.\n\n==Notable colleagues and students==\n* [[Hassan Nasrallah]]\n* [[Muhammad Hussein Fadlullah]]\n* [[Muhammad Baqir al-Hakim]] (Late)\n* [[Muhammad Muhammad Sadiq as-Sadr]]\n* [[Mohsen Araki]]\n* [[Kazem al-Haeri]]\n* [[Abbas al-Musawi]]\n* [[Talib Jauhari]]\n* [[Syed Sajid Ali Naqvi]]\n* [[Ali El-Amine]]\n* [[Allama Syed Zeeshan Haider Jawadi]]\n\n==Books==\n* ''[[Iqtisaduna]]''\n* ''[[Falsafatuna]]''\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Five Martyrs of Shia Islam]]\n*[[Shahid Awwal]]\n*[[Shahid Thani]]\n*[[Shahid Salis]]\n*[[Shahid Rabay]]\n*[[Shahid Khamis]]\n*[[Muhammad al-Tijani]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Mallat, Chibli. \"Muhammad Baqir as-Sadr.\" ''Pioneers of Islamic Revival.'' ed. Ali Rahnema. London: Zed Books, 1994\n\n{{Islamic theology}}\n{{Islamic philosophy}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sadr, Muhammad Baqir Al-}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:1980 deaths]]\n[[Category:Iraqi Shia clerics]]\n[[Category:Iraqi people of Lebanese descent]]\n[[Category:Islamic philosophers]]\n[[Category:Iraqi ayatollahs]]\n[[Category:People from Kadhimiya]]\n[[Category:Iraqi Shia Muslims]]\n[[Category:Al-Moussawi family]]\n[[Category:Islamic Dawa Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Shia Muslim scholars]]\n[[Category:Executed philosophers]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions by Iraq]]\n[[Category:Twelvers]]\n[[Category:Iraqi dissidents]]\n", "name_user": "JHunterJ", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muhammad_Baqir_al-Sadr"}
{"title_page": "Andrea Weber", "text_new": "'''Andrea Weber''' is an applied [[Labour economics|labor economist]] and currently a professor at the [[Central European University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economics.ceu.edu/people/andrea-weber|title=Andrea Weber {{!}} Department of Economics and Business|website=economics.ceu.edu|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> She is a co-editor of the [[Journal of Public Economics]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/journal-of-public-economics/editorial-board|title=Journal of Public Economics Editorial Board}}</ref>\n\nShe is a research fellow at the Institute of Labor Economics<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iza.org/person/1386/andrea-weber|title=Andrea Weber {{!}} IZA - Institute of Labor Economics|website=www.iza.org|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and a fellow at the [[Centre for Economic Policy Research|CEPR]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cepr.org/active/researchers/contact.php?IDENT=153232|title=Researcher Contact Details|website=cepr.org|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Career and education ==\nShe obtained her PhD from the Vienna University of Technology and an MA in Mathematics from the same university. Before joining the [[Central European University|CEU]], she was a Professor at [[Vienna University of Economics and Business]], the [[University of Mannheim]] and a visiting assistant professor at [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dropbox.com/s/94g223iuar6rzsc/andrea_weber_CV.pdf?dl=0|title=Andrea Weber's CV|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\nWeber's research mainly focuses on [[Labour economics|labor economics]] and [[Applied Econometrics and International Development|applied econometrics]]. Her work have been quote has been quoted 5880 times according to [[Google Scholar|Google scholar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=MAUE_ocAAAAJ&hl=en|title=Andrea Weber - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> She has published papers in the [[Quarterly Journal of Economics]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Card|first=David|last2=Chetty|first2=Raj|last3=Weber|first3=Andrea|date=2007-11-01|title=Cash-on-Hand and Competing Models of Intertemporal Behavior: New Evidence from the Labor Market|url=https://academic.oup.com/qje/article/122/4/1511/1850504|journal=The Quarterly Journal of Economics|language=en|volume=122|issue=4|pages=1511\u20131560|doi=10.1162/qjec.2007.122.4.1511|issn=0033-5533}}</ref> [[Econometrica|Econometirca]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Card|first=David|last2=Lee|first2=David S.|last3=Pei|first3=Zhuan|last4=Weber|first4=Andrea|date=2015|title=Inference on Causal Effects in a Generalized Regression Kink Design|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.3982/ECTA11224|journal=Econometrica|language=en|volume=83|issue=6|pages=2453\u20132483|doi=10.3982/ECTA11224|issn=1468-0262}}</ref> the [[The American Economic Review|American Economic Review]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chetty|first=Raj|last2=Guren|first2=Adam|last3=Manoli|first3=Day|last4=Weber|first4=Andrea|date=2011|title=Are Micro and Macro Labor Supply Elasticities Consistent? A Review of Evidence on the Intensive and Extensive Margins|url=https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/aer.101.3.471|journal=American Economic Review|language=en|volume=101|issue=3|pages=471\u2013475|doi=10.1257/aer.101.3.471|issn=0002-8282|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Card|first=David|last2=Chetty|first2=Raj|last3=Weber|first3=Andrea|date=2007|title=The Spike at Benefit Exhaustion: Leaving the Unemployment System or Starting a New Job?|url=https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/aer.97.2.113|journal=American Economic Review|language=en|volume=97|issue=2|pages=113\u2013118|doi=10.1257/aer.97.2.113|issn=0002-8282|via=}}</ref> and the [[The Economic Journal|Economic Journal]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Card|first=David|last2=Kluve|first2=Jochen|last3=Weber|first3=Andrea|date=2010|title=Active Labour Market Policy Evaluations: A Meta-Analysis*|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1468-0297.2010.02387.x|journal=The Economic Journal|language=en|volume=120|issue=548|pages=F452\u2013F477|doi=10.1111/j.1468-0297.2010.02387.x|issn=1468-0297}}</ref>\n\nHer research has been featured in [[The Economist]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/free-exchange/2015/08/17/how-governments-should-help-those-on-the-dole|title=How governments should help those on the dole|work=The Economist|access-date=2020-04-09|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> [[Quartz]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/207107/nobel-economist-gary-becker-showed-that-mike-milken-was-historys-greatest-feminist/|title=Nobel economist Gary Becker showed that Mike Milken was history\u2019s greatest feminist|last=Smith|first=Noah|website=Quartz|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> [[Vox Media|Vox]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/4/27/17281676/job-guarantee-design-bad-jobs-labor-market-federal-reserve|title=4 big questions about job guarantees|last=Matthews|first=Dylan|date=2018-04-27|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> [[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=db058330-7a2d-11ea-8bc1-b9f8dd52a3a8&url=L29waW5pb24vYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAxOC0wNy0xMC9hLXUtcy1nb3Zlcm5tZW50LWpvYi1ndWFyYW50ZWUtcHJvZ3JhbS1kZXNlcnZlcy1za2VwdGljaXNt|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and [[Die Presse]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.diepresse.com/5722925/kann-die-frauenquote-die-glaserne-decke-durchschlagen|title=Kann die Frauenquote die \"gl\u00e4serne Decke\" durchschlagen?|last=Von|first=18 11 2019 Um 08:56|last2=Weber|first2=rea|date=2019-11-18|website=Die Presse|language=de|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Selected bibliography ===\n\n* Card, David; Kluve, Jochen; Weber, Andrea (2010). \"Active Labour Market Policy Evaluations: A Meta-Analysis*\". The Economic Journal. 120 (548): F452\u2013F477.\n* Chetty, Raj; Guren, Adam; Manoli, Day; Weber, Andrea (2011). \"Are Micro and Macro Labor Supply Elasticities Consistent? A Review of Evidence on the Intensive and Extensive Margins\". American Economic Review. 101 (3): 471\u2013475.\n* Card, David; Chetty, Raj; Weber, Andrea (2007-11-01). \"Cash-on-Hand and Competing Models of Intertemporal Behavior: New Evidence from the Labor Market\". The Quarterly Journal of Economics. 122 (4): 1511\u20131560.\n* Card, David; Chetty, Raj; Weber, Andrea (2007). \"The Spike at Benefit Exhaustion: Leaving the Unemployment System or Starting a New Job?\". American Economic Review. 97 (2): 113\u2013118. \n* Card, David; Lee, David S.; Pei, Zhuan; Weber, Andrea (2015). \"Inference on Causal Effects in a Generalized Regression Kink Design\". Econometrica. 83 (6): 2453\u20132483.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Central European University]]\n[[Category:Category:Women economists]]\n[[Category:Austrian women economists]]\n[[Category:TU Wien alumni]]\n", "text_old": "Andrea Weber is an applied [[Labour economics|labor economist]] and currently a professor at the [[Central European University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economics.ceu.edu/people/andrea-weber|title=Andrea Weber {{!}} Department of Economics and Business|website=economics.ceu.edu|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> She is a co-editor of the [[Journal of Public Economics]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.journals.elsevier.com/journal-of-public-economics/editorial-board|title=Journal of Public Economics Editorial Board}}</ref>\n\nShe is a research fellow at the Institute of Labor Economics<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iza.org/person/1386/andrea-weber|title=Andrea Weber {{!}} IZA - Institute of Labor Economics|website=www.iza.org|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and a fellow at the [[Centre for Economic Policy Research|CEPR]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cepr.org/active/researchers/contact.php?IDENT=153232|title=Researcher Contact Details|website=cepr.org|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n== Career and education ==\nShe obtained her PhD from the Vienna University of Technology and an MA in Mathematics from the same university. Before joining the [[Central European University|CEU]], she was a Professor at [[Vienna University of Economics and Business]], the [[University of Mannheim]] and a visiting assistant professor at [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dropbox.com/s/94g223iuar6rzsc/andrea_weber_CV.pdf?dl=0|title=Andrea Weber's CV|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\nWeber's resarch mainly focuses on [[Labour economics|labor economics]] and [[Applied Econometrics and International Development|applied econometrics]]. Her work have been quote has been quoted 5880 times according to [[Google Scholar|Google scholar]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=MAUE_ocAAAAJ&hl=en|title=Andrea Weber - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> She has published papers in the [[Quarterly Journal of Economics]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Card|first=David|last2=Chetty|first2=Raj|last3=Weber|first3=Andrea|date=2007-11-01|title=Cash-on-Hand and Competing Models of Intertemporal Behavior: New Evidence from the Labor Market|url=https://academic.oup.com/qje/article/122/4/1511/1850504|journal=The Quarterly Journal of Economics|language=en|volume=122|issue=4|pages=1511\u20131560|doi=10.1162/qjec.2007.122.4.1511|issn=0033-5533}}</ref> [[Econometrica|Econometirca]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Card|first=David|last2=Lee|first2=David S.|last3=Pei|first3=Zhuan|last4=Weber|first4=Andrea|date=2015|title=Inference on Causal Effects in a Generalized Regression Kink Design|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.3982/ECTA11224|journal=Econometrica|language=en|volume=83|issue=6|pages=2453\u20132483|doi=10.3982/ECTA11224|issn=1468-0262}}</ref> the [[The American Economic Review|American Economic Review]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chetty|first=Raj|last2=Guren|first2=Adam|last3=Manoli|first3=Day|last4=Weber|first4=Andrea|date=2011|title=Are Micro and Macro Labor Supply Elasticities Consistent? A Review of Evidence on the Intensive and Extensive Margins|url=https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/aer.101.3.471|journal=American Economic Review|language=en|volume=101|issue=3|pages=471\u2013475|doi=10.1257/aer.101.3.471|issn=0002-8282|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Card|first=David|last2=Chetty|first2=Raj|last3=Weber|first3=Andrea|date=2007|title=The Spike at Benefit Exhaustion: Leaving the Unemployment System or Starting a New Job?|url=https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/aer.97.2.113|journal=American Economic Review|language=en|volume=97|issue=2|pages=113\u2013118|doi=10.1257/aer.97.2.113|issn=0002-8282|via=}}</ref> and the [[The Economic Journal|Economic Journal]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Card|first=David|last2=Kluve|first2=Jochen|last3=Weber|first3=Andrea|date=2010|title=Active Labour Market Policy Evaluations: A Meta-Analysis*|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1468-0297.2010.02387.x|journal=The Economic Journal|language=en|volume=120|issue=548|pages=F452\u2013F477|doi=10.1111/j.1468-0297.2010.02387.x|issn=1468-0297}}</ref>\n\nHer research has been featured in [[The Economist]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/free-exchange/2015/08/17/how-governments-should-help-those-on-the-dole|title=How governments should help those on the dole|work=The Economist|access-date=2020-04-09|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> [[Quartz]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/207107/nobel-economist-gary-becker-showed-that-mike-milken-was-historys-greatest-feminist/|title=Nobel economist Gary Becker showed that Mike Milken was history\u2019s greatest feminist|last=Smith|first=Noah|website=Quartz|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> [[Vox Media|Vox]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/4/27/17281676/job-guarantee-design-bad-jobs-labor-market-federal-reserve|title=4 big questions about job guarantees|last=Matthews|first=Dylan|date=2018-04-27|website=Vox|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> [[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/tosv2.html?vid=&uuid=db058330-7a2d-11ea-8bc1-b9f8dd52a3a8&url=L29waW5pb24vYXJ0aWNsZXMvMjAxOC0wNy0xMC9hLXUtcy1nb3Zlcm5tZW50LWpvYi1ndWFyYW50ZWUtcHJvZ3JhbS1kZXNlcnZlcy1za2VwdGljaXNt|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> and [[Die Presse]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.diepresse.com/5722925/kann-die-frauenquote-die-glaserne-decke-durchschlagen|title=Kann die Frauenquote die \u201egl\u00e4serne Decke\u201c durchschlagen?|last=Von|first=18 11 2019 Um 08:56|last2=Weber|first2=rea|date=2019-11-18|website=Die Presse|language=de|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Selected bibliography ===\n\n* Card, David; Kluve, Jochen; Weber, Andrea (2010). \"Active Labour Market Policy Evaluations: A Meta-Analysis*\". The Economic Journal. 120 (548): F452\u2013F477.\n* Chetty, Raj; Guren, Adam; Manoli, Day; Weber, Andrea (2011). \"Are Micro and Macro Labor Supply Elasticities Consistent? A Review of Evidence on the Intensive and Extensive Margins\". American Economic Review. 101 (3): 471\u2013475.\n* Card, David; Chetty, Raj; Weber, Andrea (2007-11-01). \"Cash-on-Hand and Competing Models of Intertemporal Behavior: New Evidence from the Labor Market\". The Quarterly Journal of Economics. 122 (4): 1511\u20131560.\n* Card, David; Chetty, Raj; Weber, Andrea (2007). \"The Spike at Benefit Exhaustion: Leaving the Unemployment System or Starting a New Job?\". American Economic Review. 97 (2): 113\u2013118. \n* Card, David; Lee, David S.; Pei, Zhuan; Weber, Andrea (2015). \"Inference on Causal Effects in a Generalized Regression Kink Design\". Econometrica. 83 (6): 2453\u20132483.\n\n== References ==\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Central European University]]\n[[Category:Category:Women economists]]\n[[Category:Austrian women economists]]\n[[Category:TU Wien alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment": "ApplyGen fix(es),typo(s) fixed: resarch \u2192 research", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrea_Weber"}
{"title_page": "DJ Cassidy", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist \n| name         = DJ Cassidy\n| image        = DJ Cassidy.jpg\n| image_size   = 320px\n| caption      = Photographed in 2014 by [[Lyle Owerko]]\n| background   = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_name   = Cassidy Podell\n| birth_place  = [[New York City]]\n| occupation   = [[Disc jockey|DJ]], [[record producer]], [[Master of ceremonies|MC]]\n| website      = {{URL|http://www.djcassidy.com/}}\n| associated_acts = [[R. Kelly]], [[Robin Thicke]], [[Jessie J]], [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]]\n}}\n'''Cassidy Durango Milton Willy Podell''' (born 1981), known as '''DJ Cassidy''', is an American DJ, record producer and MC.<ref name=Munday/><ref name=Berrie9July2009/>\n\nWith his trademark [[boater]]s, cricket sweaters, bow ties, color-blocked [[tuxedo]]s, and 24-carat-gold microphone, Cassidy became known for his work at celebrity functions, including the 50th birthday party and [[First inauguration of Barack Obama|2009 inauguration]] of President [[Barack Obama]], and the 2008 wedding of [[Beyonc\u00e9]] and [[Jay-Z]].<ref name=Davis2014/><ref name=Williams10March2014>Brennan Williams, [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/03/10/dj-cassidy-new-album-paradise-royale-resurgence-disco_n_4936291.html \"DJ Cassidy Shares Details On New Album, 'Paradise Royale,' And The Resurgence Of Disco\"], ''HuffPost'', 10 March 2014.</ref><ref name=Berrie9July2009>Nicole Berrie, [http://www.vanityfair.com/online/daily/2009/07/dj-cassidy-celebrates-his-birthday-with-musics-biggest-names \"D.J. Cassidy Celebrates His Birthday with Music's Biggest Names\"], ''Vanity Fair'', 9 July 2009.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in New York's [[Upper East Side]], Cassidy is the second child of Monica Podell, n\u00e9e Faust, and music agent [[Jonny Podell]]. Cassidy's sister, Brittany, was born in 1977.<ref name=Gross/> At the time of Cassidy's birth, Jonny Podell was a booking agent for Norby Walters Associates;<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=dyQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT71 \"Births\"], ''Billboard'', 8 Aug 1981, p. 72.</ref> he became head of music at [[ICM Partners|ICM]] in 1996. He and Monica Podell separated in 1982.<ref name=Gross>Michael Gross, [https://books.google.com/books?id=g-gCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA27 \"Rock 'n' Roll Revival\"], ''New York Magazine'', 30(26), 14 July 1997, pp.&nbsp;24, 27 (24\u201329).</ref>\n\nInterested in deejaying from an early age, Cassidy said he had always been a \"[[hip-hop]] kid\". As a child, he watched dance films such as [[Breakin']] and [[Breakin' 2: Electric Boogaloo]], and later loved [[Grandmaster Flash]], [[Kool Herc]], and [[Afrika Bambaataa]]. His tenth birthday present was two [[turntable]]s and a [[Mixing console|mixer]].<ref name=Davis2014/> He began by working at teenage parties, school carnivals, and talent shows then, from his senior year, in nightclubs.<ref>Lee Hawkins, [http://live.wsj.com/video/dj-cassidy-deejay-to-the-stars/BA8FC678-C9C5-4612-903E-3A5BF59E0D66.html#!BA8FC678-C9C5-4612-903E-3A5BF59E0D66 \"Deejay Cassidy: Deejay to the Death Star\"], ''Wall Street Journal'', 29 November 2011.</ref>\n\nIn 1999 he began his undergraduate studies at [[George Washington University]] before transferring to [[New York University]], where he majored in sociology and graduated in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |title=About DJ Cassidy |url=http://www.mtv.com/artists/dj-cassidy/biography/ |publisher=MTV |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423172805/http://www.mtv.com/artists/dj-cassidy/biography/ |archivedate=23 April 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>[http://www.nyualumniblog.com/2010/01/cassidy-podell-cas-03-world-renowned-dj.html \"Cassidy Podell (CAS '03) \u2013 World Renowned DJ\"], NYU Arts and Science Alumni Blog, 29 January 2010.</ref>\n\n==Performances==\nCassidy was discovered by [[Sean Combs]] while working the 10\u20134 night shift at a GQ party in the basement of Lotus, a club in Manhattan.<ref name=OneWorld>David Crowley, \"The Best Man\", ''Oneworld'', 8(1-4), 2003, p. 110.</ref><ref name=Greenburg/> Combs wrote his phone number on a napkin and asked Cassidy to call him, which led Cassidy to work at the 2001 wedding of [[Jennifer Lopez]] and [[Cris Judd]],<ref name=OneWorld/> as well as [[Grammy]] parties and the [[MTV Video Music Awards]]. As of 2011, according to ''Forbes'', Cassidy was performing 200 gigs a year, sometimes earning $100,000 a night.<ref name=Greenburg>Zack O'Malley Greenburg, [https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2011/08/09/the-incredible-business-of-hip-hops-favorite-dj-cassidy/ \"The Incredible Business of Hip-Hop's Favorite DJ\"], ''Forbes'', 9 August 2011.</ref> ''MusicRadar'' reported in 2014 that he used two [[CDJ#CDJ-2000|CDJ 2000]] digital turntables by [[Pioneer Electronics]], a Pioneer DJM-900, in-ear headphones custom-made by [[Jerry Harvey (inventor)|JH Audio]], and a 24-carat-gold microphone custom-made by [[Shure]].<ref name=Davis2014/> \n\nKnown for wearing boaters, cricket sweaters and tuxedos, often in pink and green,<ref>Hilary Hughes, [http://www.esquire.com/style/mens-fashion/a24457/dj-cassidy-tailor-vma-2013/ \"A Trip to the Tailor with DJ Cassidy\"], ''Esquire'', 26 August 2013.</ref> Cassidy worked at parties hosted by [[Oprah Winfrey]] and [[Anna Wintour]] and at the weddings of [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Jennifer Lopez]], and [[Kim Kardashian]].<ref name=Vega/><ref name=Greenburg/> After he worked at the opening party in 2009 for Oprah Winfrey's girls' school in South Africa, she recommended him to the Obamas.<ref>{{cite web |title=Oprah Recommended Obama\u2019s Inaugural DJ |url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/entertainment/celebrity/Oprah_Recommended_Obama_s_Inaugural_DJ.html |publisher=NBC Washington |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304114208/http://www.nbcwashington.com/entertainment/celebrity/Oprah_Recommended_Obama_s_Inaugural_DJ.html |archivedate=4 March 2016 |date=14 July 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref> This led to him working at President Obama's first inauguration ball in 2009, at the president's and [[Michelle Obama]]'s 50th birthday parties, and at the 2012 [[Democratic National Convention]].<ref name=Vega>Cecilia Vega and Eric Johnson, [http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2012/09/dj-cassidy-keeps-dnc-rockin-obamas-spin-master-behind-the-scenes/ \"DJ Cassidy Keeps DNC Rockin': Obama\u2019s Spin Master Behind the Scenes\"], ABC News, 6 September 2012.</ref>\n\n==Music==\n===Singles===\n[[File:NileRodgers2012.png|thumb|alt=photograph|On [[Calling All Hearts (song)|Calling All Hearts]]\", [[Nile Rodgers]] of [[Chic (band)|Chic]] played the same guitar as on Chic's \"[[Good Times (Chic song)|Good Times]]\" and [[Sister Sledge]]'s \"[[We Are Family (song)|We Are Family]]\".]]\nCassidy said in 2013 that he was working on his first album, ''Paradise Royale'', which would capture the architecture of 1978\u20131982 dance music; he called this \"the greatest and most universal dance music of all time\".<ref name=Luerssen16Dec2013>John D. Luerssen, [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/dj-cassidy-salutes-classic-dance-music-premiere-20131216 \"DJ Cassidy Salutes Classic Dance Music&nbsp;\u2013 Premiere\"], ''Rolling Stone'', 16 December 2013.</ref><ref name=Munday>Matt Munday, [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/mr-disco-friend-to-the-obamas-beyonc-and-oprah-dj-cassidy-is-now-cosying-up-to-the-sound-of-the-1970s-9174994.html \"Mr disco: Friend to the Obamas, Beyonc\u00e9 and Oprah, DJ Cassidy is now cosying up to the sound of the 1970s\"], ''The Independent'', 9 March 2014.</ref> He planned to bring together a 14-piece [[string section]] and 22 of the world's most notable musicians from that period.<ref name=bio>[http://www.djcassidy.com/bio/ \"Bio\"], djcassidy.com.</ref><ref name=Graff>Gary Graff, [http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5869793/dj-cassidy-paradise-royale-album-unites-rb-dance-legends-with-newer-stars \"DJ Cassidy's 'Paradise Royale' Album Unites R&B Dance Legends With Newer Stars\"], ''Billboard'', 16 January 2014.</ref><ref>[http://www.rap-up.com/2014/01/16/dj-cassidy-enlists-r-kelly-usher-kelly-rowland-for-paradise-royale/ \"DJ Cassidy Enlists R. Kelly, Usher, & Kelly Rowland for \u2018Paradise Royale\u2019\"], ''Rap-Up'', accessed 11 March 2014.</ref> He created an [[#playlist|iTunes playlist of 25 songs]] recorded between 1978 and 1982, then tried to make his music sound like those songs. He realized that the producers had repeatedly used the same musicians. Those are the musicians he sought to recruit.<ref name=Munday/>\n\nThe first single, \"[[Calling All Hearts (song)|Calling All Hearts]]\", sung by [[Robin Thicke]] and [[Jessie J]], was released in the US on iTunes in February 2014.<ref>[https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/calling-all-hearts-feat.-robin/id816512171 \"Calling All Hearts (feat. Robin Thicke & Jessie J) - Single\"], iTunes.</ref> It featured [[Nile Rodgers]] on guitar, [[Verdine White]] on bass, [[Philip Bailey]] on percussion and background vocals, [[Larry Dunn]] on keyboards, [[John Robinson (drummer)|John \"JR\" Robinson]] on drums, and [[Jerry Hey]] on horns and strings. The video, with a 13-piece band performing on a pink heart-shaped stage, was directed by [[Director X]] and shot in London.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tZy5E6ILvEA \"DJ Cassidy \u2013 Calling All Hearts, ft. Robin Thicke, Jessie J\"], ''YouTube''; [http://directorxfilms.com/directorx.html \"Music videos\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313213940/http://directorxfilms.com/directorx.html |date=March 13, 2014 }}, directorxfilms, accessed 14 March 2015.</ref>\n\nDirector X also directed the video for Cassidy's second single, \"Make the World Go Round\", which was shot on an [[elevated train]] in Chicago. Featuring [[R. Kelly]], the single was released in the US in April 2014.<ref name=Davis2014>Claire Davis, [http://www.musicradar.com/news/dj/all-aboard-the-soul-train-with-dj-cassidy-598124/ \"All aboard the soul train with DJ Cassidy\"], ''MusicRadar'', undated 2014.</ref><ref>Edwin Ortitz, [http://www.complex.com/music/2014/03/dj-cassidy-f-r-kelly-make-the-world-go-round \"DJ Cassidy Links Up With R. Kelly on His Groovy New Single 'Make the World Go Round'\"], ''Complex'', 27 March 2014.</ref> On \"Calling All Hearts\", Nile Rodgers played the same guitar as on [[Chic (band)|Chic]]'s \"[[Good Times (Chic song)|Good Times]]\" and [[Sister Sledge]]'s \"[[We Are Family (song)|We Are Family]]\". On \"Make the World Go Round\", [[Leon \"Ndugu\" Chancler|Ndugu Chancler]] used the same drums as on [[Michael Jackson]]'s \"[[Billie Jean]]\".<ref name=Davis2014/>\n\n===Discography===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Single\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"7\"| Chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;| [[Dance Club Songs|US<br>Dance]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/DJ-Cassidy/chart-history/dance-club-play-songs|accessdate=31 January 2019|title=DJ Cassidy Chart History|work=Billboard}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL<br>(FL)<br>(Tip)]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/song/12ae59/DJ-Cassidy-feat.-Robin-Thicke-&-Jessie-J-Calling-All-Hearts|accessdate=31 January 2019|title=DJ Cassidy feat. Robin Thicke & Jessie J \u2013 Calling All Hearts|website=ultratop.be}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL<br>(WA)<br>(Tip)]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/song/12ae59/DJ-Cassidy-feat.-Robin-Thicke-&-Jessie-J-Calling-All-Hearts|accessdate=31 January 2019|title=DJ Cassidy feat. Robin Thicke & Jessie J \u2013 Calling All Hearts|website=ultratop.be}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Scottish Singles Chart|SCO]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-singles-chart/20140427/41/|accessdate=31 January 2019|title=Official Scottish Singles Sales Chart Top 100 |publisher=Official Charts Company}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Calling All Hearts (song)|Calling All Hearts]]\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(featuring [[Jessie J]] and [[Robin Thicke]])</span>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2014\n| 9 || 6 || 14 || 7 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Make the World Go Round\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(featuring [[R. Kelly]])</span>\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Future Is Mine\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(featuring [[Chromeo]])</span>\n| 2015\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Kill the Lights (Alex Newell and DJ Cassidy song)|Kill the Lights]]\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(with [[Alex Newell]] and [[Jess Glynne]], featuring [[Nile Rodgers]])</span><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7333912/audien-remix-alex-newell-jess-glynne-dj-cassidy-kill-the-lights |title = Audien Remixes DJ Cassidy's 'Kill the Lights,' Feat. Alex Newell, Jess Glynne & Nile Rodgers: Exclusive Premiere |work=Billboard |date=4 April 2016}}</ref> \n| 2016\n| 1 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Honor\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(featuring [[Grace (Australian singer)|Grace]] and [[Lil Yachty]])</span><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/honor-feat-grace-lil-yachty-single/id1222137321|title=Honor (single)|publisher=iTunes Australia}}</ref> \n| 2017\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 \n|-\n|}\n\n===Cassidy's 2104 iTunes playlist{{anchor|playlist}}===\n{{refbegin|26em}}\n#[[One Way (American band)|One Way]] and [[Alicia Myers]], \"I Want to Thank You\" (MCA, 1981)\n#[[Aretha Franklin]], \"[[Jump to It (song)|Jump to It]]\" (Arista, 1982)\n#[[The Brothers Johnson]], \"[[Stomp! (Brothers Johnson song)|Stomp!]]\" (A&M, 1980)\n#[[Central Line (band)|Central Line]], \"Walking into Sunshine\" (Mercury, 1981)\n#[[Chaka Khan]] and [[Rufus (band)|Rufus]], \"[[Do You Love What You Feel]]\" (ABC, 1979)\n#[[Change (band)|Change]], \"[[The Glow of Love]]\" (Warner Bros, 1980)\n#[[Cheryl Lynn]], \"[[Got to Be Real]]\" (Columbia, 1978)\n#[[Diana Ross]], \"[[I'm Coming Out]]\" (Motown, 1980)\n#[[Earth Wind and Fire]], \"[[Let's Groove]]\" (Columbia, 1981)\n#[[Evelyn \"Champagne\" King]], \"[[I'm in Love (Evelyn King song)|I\u2019m in Love]]\" (RCA, 1981)\n#[[First Choice (band)|First Choice]], \"Love Thang\" (Gold Mind Records, 1979)\n#[[George Benson]], \"[[Give Me the Night (George Benson song)|Give Me the Night]]\" (Warner Bros, 1980)\n#[[GQ (band)|GQ]], \"[[Disco Nights (Rock-Freak)]]\" (Arista, 1979)\n#[[Kool & the Gang]], [[Too Hot (Kool & the Gang song)|Too Hot]]\" (De-Lite, 1979)\n#[[Luther Vandross]], \"[[Never Too Much (song)|Never Too Much]]\" (Epic, 1981)\n#[[Frankie Beverly]] and [[Maze (band)|Maze]], \"[[Before I Let Go]]\" (Capitol, 1981)\n#[[Michael Jackson]], \"[[Rock with You]]\" (Epic, 1979)\n#[[Patrice Rushen]], \"[[Forget Me Nots]]\" (Elektra, 1982)\n#[[Rick James]], [[You and I (Rick James song)|\"You & I\"]] (Gordy, 1978)\n#[[Roberta Flack]] with [[Donny Hathaway]], [[Roberta Flack Featuring Donny Hathaway|\"Back Together Again\"]] (Atlantic, 1979)\n#[[Shalamar]], [[The Second Time Around (Shalamar song)|\"The Second Time Around\"]] (Solar, 1979)\n#[[Sister Sledge]], \"[[We Are Family (song)|We are Family]]\" (Atlantic, 1979)\n#[[Stevie Wonder]], \"[[Do I Do]]\" (Tamla/Motown, 1982)\n#[[Teena Marie]], \"[[Square Biz]]\" (Motown, 1981)\n#[[Chic (band)|Chic]], \"[[I Want Your Love (Chic song)|I Want Your Love]]\" (Atlantic, 1978)<ref name=Munday/>\n{{refend}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of club DJs]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140311193304/http://www.djcassidy.com/home/ Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cassidy, DJ}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:American DJs]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}}\n{{Infobox musical artist \n| name         = DJ Cassidy\n| image        = DJ Cassidy.jpg\n| image_size   = 320px\n| caption      = Photographed in 2014 by [[Lyle Owerko]]\n| background   = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_name   = Cassidy Podell\n| birth_place  = [[New York City]]\n| occupation   = [[Disc jockey|DJ]], [[record producer]], [[Master of ceremonies|MC]]\n| website      = {{URL|http://www.djcassidy.com/}}\n| associated_acts = [[R. Kelly]], [[Robin Thicke]], [[Jessie J]], [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]]\n}}\n'''Cassidy Durango Milton Willy Podell''' (born 1981), known as '''DJ Cassidy''', is an American DJ, record producer and MC.<ref name=Munday/><ref name=Berrie9July2009/>\n\nWith his trademark [[boater]]s, cricket sweaters, bow ties, color-blocked [[tuxedo]]s, and 24-carat-gold microphone, Cassidy became known for his work at celebrity functions, including the 50th birthday party and [[First inauguration of Barack Obama|2009 inauguration]] of President [[Barack Obama]], and the 2008 wedding of [[Beyonc\u00e9]] and [[Jay-Z]].<ref name=Davis2014/><ref name=Williams10March2014>Brennan Williams, [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/03/10/dj-cassidy-new-album-paradise-royale-resurgence-disco_n_4936291.html \"DJ Cassidy Shares Details On New Album, 'Paradise Royale,' And The Resurgence Of Disco\"], ''HuffPost'', 10 March 2014.</ref><ref name=Berrie9July2009>Nicole Berrie, [http://www.vanityfair.com/online/daily/2009/07/dj-cassidy-celebrates-his-birthday-with-musics-biggest-names \"D.J. Cassidy Celebrates His Birthday with Music's Biggest Names\"], ''Vanity Fair'', 9 July 2009.</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in New York's [[Upper East Side]], Cassidy is the second child of Monica Podell, n\u00e9e Faust, and music agent [[Jonny Podell]]. Cassidy's sister, Brittany, was born in 1977.<ref name=Gross/> At the time of Cassidy's birth, Jonny Podell was a booking agent for Norby Walters Associates;<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=dyQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT71 \"Births\"], ''Billboard'', 8 Aug 1981, p. 72.</ref> he became head of music at [[ICM Partners|ICM]] in 1996. He and Monica Podell separated in 1982.<ref name=Gross>Michael Gross, [https://books.google.com/books?id=g-gCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA27 \"Rock 'n' Roll Revival\"], ''New York Magazine'', 30(26), 14 July 1997, pp.&nbsp;24, 27 (24\u201329).</ref>\n\nInterested in deejaying from an early age, Cassidy said he had always been a \"[[hip-hop]] kid\". As a child, he watched dance films such as [[Breakin']] and [[Breakin' 2: Electric Boogaloo]], and later loved [[Grandmaster Flash]], [[Kool Herc]], and [[Afrika Bambaataa]]. His tenth birthday present was two [[turntable]]s and a [[Mixing console|mixer]].<ref name=Davis2014/> He began by working at teenage parties, school carnivals, and talent shows then, from his senior year, in nightclubs.<ref>Lee Hawkins, [http://live.wsj.com/video/dj-cassidy-deejay-to-the-stars/BA8FC678-C9C5-4612-903E-3A5BF59E0D66.html#!BA8FC678-C9C5-4612-903E-3A5BF59E0D66 \"Deejay Cassidy: Deejay to the Death Star\"], ''Wall Street Journal'', 29 November 2011.</ref>\n\nIn 1999 he began his undergraduate studies at [[George Washington University]] before transferring to [[New York University]], where he majored in sociology and graduated in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |title=About DJ Cassidy |url=http://www.mtv.com/artists/dj-cassidy/biography/ |publisher=MTV |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423172805/http://www.mtv.com/artists/dj-cassidy/biography/ |archivedate=23 April 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>[http://www.nyualumniblog.com/2010/01/cassidy-podell-cas-03-world-renowned-dj.html \"Cassidy Podell (CAS '03) \u2013 World Renowned DJ\"], NYU Arts and Science Alumni Blog, 29 January 2010.</ref>\n\n==Performances==\nCassidy was discovered by [[Sean Combs]] while working the 10\u20134 night shift at a GQ party in the basement of Lotus, a club in Manhattan.<ref name=OneWorld>David Crowley, \"The Best Man\", ''Oneworld'', 8(1-4), 2003, p. 110.</ref><ref name=Greenburg/> Combs wrote his phone number on a napkin and asked Cassidy to call him, which led Cassidy to work at the 2001 wedding of [[Jennifer Lopez]] and [[Cris Judd]],<ref name=OneWorld/> as well as [[Grammy]] parties and the [[MTV Video Music Awards]]. As of 2011, according to ''Forbes'', Cassidy was performing 200 gigs a year, sometimes earning $100,000 a night.<ref name=Greenburg>Zack O'Malley Greenburg, [https://www.forbes.com/sites/zackomalleygreenburg/2011/08/09/the-incredible-business-of-hip-hops-favorite-dj-cassidy/ \"The Incredible Business of Hip-Hop's Favorite DJ\"], ''Forbes'', 9 August 2011.</ref> ''MusicRadar'' reported in 2014 that he used two [[CDJ#CDJ-2000|CDJ 2000]] digital turntables by [[Pioneer Electronics]], a Pioneer DJM-900, in-ear headphones custom-made by [[Jerry Harvey (inventor)|JH Audio]], and a 24-carat-gold microphone custom-made by [[Shure]].<ref name=Davis2014/> \n\nKnown for wearing boaters, cricket sweaters and tuxedos, often in pink and green,<ref>Hilary Hughes, [http://www.esquire.com/style/mens-fashion/a24457/dj-cassidy-tailor-vma-2013/ \"A Trip to the Tailor with DJ Cassidy\"], ''Esquire'', 26 August 2013.</ref> Cassidy worked at parties hosted by [[Oprah Winfrey]] and [[Anna Wintour]] and at the weddings of [[Beyonc\u00e9]], [[Jennifer Lopez]], and [[Kim Kardashian]].<ref name=Vega/><ref name=Greenburg/> After he worked at the opening party in 2009 for Oprah Winfrey's girls' school in South Africa, she recommended him to the Obamas.<ref>{{cite web |title=Oprah Recommended Obama\u2019s Inaugural DJ |url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/entertainment/celebrity/Oprah_Recommended_Obama_s_Inaugural_DJ.html |publisher=NBC Washington |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304114208/http://www.nbcwashington.com/entertainment/celebrity/Oprah_Recommended_Obama_s_Inaugural_DJ.html |archivedate=4 March 2016 |date=14 July 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref> This led to him working at President Obama's first inauguration ball in 2009, at the president's and [[Michelle Obama]]'s 50th birthday parties, and at the 2012 [[Democratic National Convention]].<ref name=Vega>Cecilia Vega and Eric Johnson, [http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2012/09/dj-cassidy-keeps-dnc-rockin-obamas-spin-master-behind-the-scenes/ \"DJ Cassidy Keeps DNC Rockin': Obama\u2019s Spin Master Behind the Scenes\"], ABC News, 6 September 2012.</ref>\n\n==Music==\n===Singles===\n[[File:NileRodgers2012.png|thumb|alt=photograph|On [[Calling All Hearts (song)|Calling All Hearts]]\", [[Nile Rodgers]] of [[Chic (band)|Chic]] played the same guitar as on Chic's \"[[Good Times (Chic song)|Good Times]]\" and [[Sister Sledge]]'s \"[[We Are Family (song)|We Are Family]]\".]]\nCassidy said in 2013 that he was working on his first album, ''Paradise Royale'', which would capture the architecture of 1978\u20131982 dance music; he called this \"the greatest and most universal dance music of all time\".<ref name=Luerssen16Dec2013>John D. Luerssen, [https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/dj-cassidy-salutes-classic-dance-music-premiere-20131216 \"DJ Cassidy Salutes Classic Dance Music&nbsp;\u2013 Premiere\"], ''Rolling Stone'', 16 December 2013.</ref><ref name=Munday>Matt Munday, [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/mr-disco-friend-to-the-obamas-beyonc-and-oprah-dj-cassidy-is-now-cosying-up-to-the-sound-of-the-1970s-9174994.html \"Mr disco: Friend to the Obamas, Beyonc\u00e9 and Oprah, DJ Cassidy is now cosying up to the sound of the 1970s\"], ''The Independent'', 9 March 2014.</ref> He planned to bring together a 14-piece [[string section]] and 22 of the world's most notable musicians from that period.<ref name=bio>[http://www.djcassidy.com/bio/ \"Bio\"], djcassidy.com.</ref><ref name=Graff>Gary Graff, [http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/5869793/dj-cassidy-paradise-royale-album-unites-rb-dance-legends-with-newer-stars \"DJ Cassidy's 'Paradise Royale' Album Unites R&B Dance Legends With Newer Stars\"], ''Billboard'', 16 January 2014.</ref><ref>[http://www.rap-up.com/2014/01/16/dj-cassidy-enlists-r-kelly-usher-kelly-rowland-for-paradise-royale/ \"DJ Cassidy Enlists R. Kelly, Usher, & Kelly Rowland for \u2018Paradise Royale\u2019\"], ''Rap-Up'', accessed 11 March 2014.</ref> He created an [[#playlist|iTunes playlist of 25 songs]] recorded between 1978 and 1982, then tried to make his music sound like those songs. He realized that the producers had repeatedly used the same musicians. Those are the musicians he sought to recruit.<ref name=Munday/>\n\nThe first single, \"[[Calling All Hearts (song)|Calling All Hearts]]\", sung by [[Robin Thicke]] and [[Jessie J]], was released in the US on iTunes in February 2014.<ref>[https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/calling-all-hearts-feat.-robin/id816512171 \"Calling All Hearts (feat. Robin Thicke & Jessie J) - Single\"], iTunes.</ref> It featured [[Nile Rodgers]] on guitar, [[Verdine White]] on bass, [[Philip Bailey]] on percussion and background vocals, [[Larry Dunn]] on keyboards, [[John Robinson (drummer)|John \"JR\" Robinson]] on drums, and [[Jerry Hey]] on horns and strings. The video, with a 13-piece band performing on a pink heart-shaped stage, was directed by [[Director X]] and shot in London.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tZy5E6ILvEA \"DJ Cassidy \u2013 Calling All Hearts, ft. Robin Thicke, Jessie J\"], ''YouTube''; [http://directorxfilms.com/directorx.html \"Music videos\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313213940/http://directorxfilms.com/directorx.html |date=March 13, 2014 }}, directorxfilms, accessed 14 March 2015.</ref>\n\nDirector X also directed the video for Cassidy's second single, \"Make the World Go Round\", which was shot on an [[elevated train]] in Chicago. Featuring [[R. Kelly]], the single was released in the US in April 2014.<ref name=Davis2014>Claire Davis, [http://www.musicradar.com/news/dj/all-aboard-the-soul-train-with-dj-cassidy-598124/ \"All aboard the soul train with DJ Cassidy\"], ''MusicRadar'', undated 2014.</ref><ref>Edwin Ortitz, [http://www.complex.com/music/2014/03/dj-cassidy-f-r-kelly-make-the-world-go-round \"DJ Cassidy Links Up With R. Kelly on His Groovy New Single 'Make the World Go Round'\"], ''Complex'', 27 March 2014.</ref> On \"Calling All Hearts\", Nile Rodgers played the same guitar as on [[Chic (band)|Chic]]'s \"[[Good Times (Chic song)|Good Times]]\" and [[Sister Sledge]]'s \"[[We Are Family (song)|We Are Family]]\". On \"Make the World Go Round\", [[Leon \"Ndugu\" Chancler|Ndugu Chancler]] used the same drums as on [[Michael Jackson]]'s \"[[Billie Jean]]\".<ref name=Davis2014/>\n\n===Discography===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Single\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"7\"| Chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;| [[Dance Club Songs|US<br>Dance]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/DJ-Cassidy/chart-history/dance-club-play-songs|accessdate=31 January 2019|title=DJ Cassidy Chart History|work=Billboard}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL<br>(FL)<br>(Tip)]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/song/12ae59/DJ-Cassidy-feat.-Robin-Thicke-&-Jessie-J-Calling-All-Hearts|accessdate=31 January 2019|title=DJ Cassidy feat. Robin Thicke & Jessie J \u2013 Calling All Hearts|website=ultratop.be}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL<br>(WA)<br>(Tip)]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/song/12ae59/DJ-Cassidy-feat.-Robin-Thicke-&-Jessie-J-Calling-All-Hearts|accessdate=31 January 2019|title=DJ Cassidy feat. Robin Thicke & Jessie J \u2013 Calling All Hearts|website=ultratop.be}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Scottish Singles Chart|SCO]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-singles-chart/20140427/41/|accessdate=31 January 2019|title=Official Scottish Singles Sales Chart Top 100 |publisher=Official Charts Company}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Calling All Hearts (song)|Calling All Hearts]]\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(featuring [[Jessie J]] and [[Robin Thicke]])</span>\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2014\n| 9 || 6 || 14 || 7 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Make the World Go Round\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(featuring [[R. Kelly]])</span>\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Future Is Mine\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(featuring [[Chromeo]])</span>\n| 2015\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Kill the Lights (Alex Newell and DJ Cassidy song)|Kill the Lights]]\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(with [[Alex Newell]] and [[Jess Glynne]], featuring [[Nile Rodgers]])</span><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7333912/audien-remix-alex-newell-jess-glynne-dj-cassidy-kill-the-lights |title = Audien Remixes DJ Cassidy's 'Kill the Lights,' Feat. Alex Newell, Jess Glynne & Nile Rodgers: Exclusive Premiere |work=Billboard |date=4 April 2016}}</ref> \n| 2016\n| 1 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Honor\"<br/><span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(featuring [[Grace (Australian singer)|Grace]] and [[Lil Yachty]])</span><ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/honor-feat-grace-lil-yachty-single/id1222137321|title=Honor (single)|publisher=iTunes Australia}}</ref> \n| 2017\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 \n|-\n|}\n\n===Cassidy's 2104 iTunes playlist{{anchor|playlist}}===\n{{refbegin|26em}}\n#[[One Way (American band)|One Way]] and [[Alicia Myers]], \"I Want to Thank You\" (MCA, 1981)\n#[[Aretha Franklin]], \"[[Jump to It (song)|Jump to It]]\" (Arista, 1982)\n#[[The Brothers Johnson]], \"[[Stomp!]]\" (A&M, 1980)\n#[[Central Line (band)|Central Line]], \"Walking into Sunshine\" (Mercury, 1981)\n#[[Chaka Khan]] and [[Rufus (band)|Rufus]], \"[[Do You Love What You Feel]]\" (ABC, 1979)\n#[[Change (band)|Change]], \"[[The Glow of Love]]\" (Warner Bros, 1980)\n#[[Cheryl Lynn]], \"[[Got to Be Real]]\" (Columbia, 1978)\n#[[Diana Ross]], \"[[I'm Coming Out]]\" (Motown, 1980)\n#[[Earth Wind and Fire]], \"[[Let's Groove]]\" (Columbia, 1981)\n#[[Evelyn \"Champagne\" King]], \"[[I'm in Love (Evelyn King song)|I\u2019m in Love]]\" (RCA, 1981)\n#[[First Choice (band)|First Choice]], \"Love Thang\" (Gold Mind Records, 1979)\n#[[George Benson]], \"[[Give Me the Night (George Benson song)|Give Me the Night]]\" (Warner Bros, 1980)\n#[[GQ (band)|GQ]], \"[[Disco Nights (Rock-Freak)]]\" (Arista, 1979)\n#[[Kool & the Gang]], [[Too Hot (Kool & the Gang song)|Too Hot]]\" (De-Lite, 1979)\n#[[Luther Vandross]], \"[[Never Too Much (song)|Never Too Much]]\" (Epic, 1981)\n#[[Frankie Beverly]] and [[Maze (band)|Maze]], \"[[Before I Let Go]]\" (Capitol, 1981)\n#[[Michael Jackson]], \"[[Rock with You]]\" (Epic, 1979)\n#[[Patrice Rushen]], \"[[Forget Me Nots]]\" (Elektra, 1982)\n#[[Rick James]], [[You and I (Rick James song)|\"You & I\"]] (Gordy, 1978)\n#[[Roberta Flack]] with [[Donny Hathaway]], [[Roberta Flack Featuring Donny Hathaway|\"Back Together Again\"]] (Atlantic, 1979)\n#[[Shalamar]], [[The Second Time Around (Shalamar song)|\"The Second Time Around\"]] (Solar, 1979)\n#[[Sister Sledge]], \"[[We Are Family (song)|We are Family]]\" (Atlantic, 1979)\n#[[Stevie Wonder]], \"[[Do I Do]]\" (Tamla/Motown, 1982)\n#[[Teena Marie]], \"[[Square Biz]]\" (Motown, 1981)\n#[[Chic (band)|Chic]], \"[[I Want Your Love (Chic song)|I Want Your Love]]\" (Atlantic, 1978)<ref name=Munday/>\n{{refend}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of club DJs]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140311193304/http://www.djcassidy.com/home/ Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cassidy, DJ}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:American 