{"title_page": "Woisika language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Woisika\n|nativename=''Kamang''\n|states=[[Indonesia]]\n|region=[[Alor Island]]\n|speakers=6,000\n|date=2014\n|ref=<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/culture/languages-atlas/en/atlasmap/language-id-2745.html|title=UNESCO Atlas of the World's Languages in danger|website=www.unesco.org|language=en|access-date=2018-06-06}}</ref>\n|familycolor=Papuan\n|fam1=[[Trans\u2013New Guinea]] ?\n|fam2=[[West Bomberai languages|West Bomberai]] ?\n|fam3=[[Timor\u2013Alor\u2013Pantar languages|Timor\u2013Alor\u2013Pantar]]\n|fam4=[[Alor\u2013Pantar languages|Alor\u2013Pantar]]\n|fam5=[[Alor languages|Alor]]\n|iso3=woi\n|glotto=kama1365\n|glottorefname=Kamang\n}}\n'''Woisika''', also known as '''Kamang''', is a [[Papuan language]] of [[Alor Island]] of [[Indonesia]]. The three main dialects are Western Kamang, Lowland Kamang, and Upland Kamang. Dialects also include Lembur, Sibo, Kamang, Tiayai, Watang, Kamana-Kamang. They may constitute more than one language. Kamang is an [[endangered language]], since children usually only have passive competence of the language, and instead are shifting to [[Malay language|Malay]].<ref name=\"Schapper\" />\n\nSpeakers may prefer the term ''Kamang'' to refer to the speech community as a whole; ''Woisika'' is a village name.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://ausil.org.au/sites/ausil/files/1997%20Grimes%20etal%20Nusa%20Teng%20Guide.pdf|title=A guide to the people and languages of Nusa Tenggara|last=Grimes|first=Charles|publisher=Artha Wacana Press|year=1997|isbn=|location=Kupang|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Phonology==\n\n===Consonants===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=text-align:center\n|-\n|+Woisika consonant phonemes\n! colspan=2| \n! [[Labial consonant|Bilabial]]\n! [[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n! [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n! [[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n! [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|-\n! colspan=2| [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]]\n| {{IPAlink|m}}\n| {{IPAlink|n}}\n| \n| {{IPAlink|\u014b}} <ng>\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=2| [[Stop consonant|Plosive]]\n! <small>[[voicelessness|voiceless]]</small>\n| {{IPAlink|p}}\n| {{IPAlink|t}}\n|\n| {{IPAlink|k}}\n| ({{IPAlink|\u0294}}) <'>\n|-\n! <small>[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]</small>\n| {{IPAlink|b}}\n| {{IPAlink|d}}\n|\n| {{IPAlink|\u0261}}\n|\n|-\n! colspan=2| [[Fricative consonant|Fricative]]\n| {{IPAlink|\u0278}} <f>\n| {{IPAlink|s}}\n|\n|\n| ({{IPAlink|h}})\n|-\n! colspan=2| [[Approximant consonant|Approximant]]\n| {{IPAlink|w}}\n| \n| {{IPAlink|j}} <y>\n| \n|\n|-\n! colspan=2| [[Lateral consonant|Lateral]]\n| \n| {{IPAlink|l}}\n|\n| \n|\n|}\n\n/h/ and /\u0294/ are marginal. /r/ is rare in initial and final position. Word-final /s/ is only in loan words.\n\nThe consonant /\u014b/ is not found word-initially, and /f/ is not found word-finally.<ref name=\"Phonemics\">{{cite book |last1=Stokhof |first1=W.A.L. |title=Woisika II Phonemics |date=1979 |publisher=Australian National University|url=https://openresearch-repository.anu.edu.au/bitstream/1885/146505/1/PL-B59.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Vowels===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+caption | '''Woisika vowel phonemes'''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! \n! colspan=2 | [[Front vowel|Front]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Central vowel|Central]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Back vowel|Back]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Close vowel|Close]]\n| {{IPAlink|i}}\n| {{IPAlink|i\u02d0}} <ii>\n|colspan=2|\n| {{IPAlink|u}}\n| {{IPAlink|u\u02d0}} <uu>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Mid vowel|Mid]]\n| {{IPAlink|e}} \n| {{IPAlink|e\u02d0}} <ee> \n|colspan=2|\n| {{IPAlink|o}}\n| {{IPAlink|o\u02d0}} <oo> \n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Open vowel|Open]]\n|colspan=2|\n| {{IPAlink|a}}\n| {{IPAlink|a\u02d0}} <aa> \n|colspan=2|\n|}\n\n==Grammar==\n\n===Serial Verb Constructions===\n\nKamang has [[serial verb construction]]s.\n\n:{| \n|''Mooi''||''bong''||''nok''||''kok''||''silang''||''dii''<ref name=\"Schapper\" />{{rp|345}}\n|-\n|banana||tree||one||fall.down||descend||lie\n|-\n|colspan=6|'A banana tree came falling down.'\n|}\n\n\n:{| \n|''Afunaa''||''yakii''||''me''||''noowaai.''<ref name=\"Schapper\" />{{rp|348}}\n|-\n|a-funaa||ga-kii||me||noo-waai.||\n|-\n|{{small|3.PAT}}-face||{{small|3.PAT}}-turn||come||{{small|3.AST}}-face\n|-\n|colspan=6|'Turn and face me.'\n|}\n\n===Valence===\n\nExamples with avalent, monovalent, bivalent, and trivalent verbs are shown below.<ref name=\"Schapper\">{{cite book |author1=Schapper, Antoinette |editor1-last=Schapper |editor1-first=Antoinette |title=The Papuan Languages of Timor, Alor and Pantar: Volume 1: Sketch Grammars |date=2014 |publisher=Walter de Gruyter |pages=287-349 |chapter=Kamang}}</ref>\n\nAvalent\n\n:{| \n|''Itunma''<ref name=\"Schapper\" />{{rp|300}}\n|-\n|itun-ma\n|-\n|late.afternoon-{{small|PFV}}\n|-\n|colspan=6|'It's late afternoon.'\n|}\n\nMonovalent\n\n:{| \n|''Markus''||''gamanteima''<ref name=\"Schapper\" />{{rp|301}}\n|-\n|Markus||ga-mantei-ma\n|-\n|Markus||{{small|3.PAT}}-thirst-{{small|PFV}}\n|-\n|colspan=6|'Markus is thirsty already.'\n|}\n\nBivalent\n\n:{| \n|''Na''||''Markus''||''gatakma.''<ref name=\"Schapper\" />{{rp|301}}\n|-\n|na||Markus||ga-tak-ma\n|-\n|{{small|1SG.AGT}}||Markus||{{small|3.PAT}}-see-{{small|PFV}}\n|-\n|colspan=6|'I have seen Markus'\n|}\n\nTrivalent\n\n:{| \n|''Markus''||''patei''||''me''||''dumma''||''wotulen.''<ref name=\"Schapper\" />{{rp|301}}\n|-\n|Markus||patei||me||dum=a||go-tulen\n|-\n|Markus||corn||{{small|TAKE}}||child={{small|SPEC}}||{{small|3.LOC}}-divide\n|-\n|colspan=6|'Markus divides corn amongst the children.'\n|}\n\n==Riddles==\nWoisika riddles relate to animals, the human body, human artifacts, natural phenomena, crops and other foods, among others.<ref name=\"Riddles\">{{cite book |last1=Stokhof |first1=W.A.L. |title=Woisika Riddles |date=1982 |publisher=Australian National University|url=https://openresearch-repository.anu.edu.au/bitstream/1885/145070/1/PL-D41.pdf}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{West Trans\u2013New Guinea languages}}\n\n[[Category:Alor\u2013Pantar languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Indonesia]]\n\n{{TNG-lang-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Woisika\n|nativename=Kamang\n|states=[[Indonesia]]\n|region=[[Alor Island]]\n|speakers=6,000\n|date=2014\n|ref=<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/culture/languages-atlas/en/atlasmap/language-id-2745.html|title=UNESCO Atlas of the World's Languages in danger|website=www.unesco.org|language=en|access-date=2018-06-06}}</ref>\n|familycolor=Papuan\n|fam1=[[Trans\u2013New Guinea]] ?\n|fam2=[[West Bomberai languages|West Bomberai]] ?\n|fam3=[[Timor\u2013Alor\u2013Pantar languages|Timor\u2013Alor\u2013Pantar]]\n|fam4=[[Alor\u2013Pantar languages|Alor\u2013Pantar]]\n|fam5=[[Alor languages|Alor]]\n|iso3=woi\n|glotto=kama1365\n|glottorefname=Kamang\n}}\n'''Woisika''', also known as '''Kamang''', is a [[Papuan language]] of [[Alor Island]] of [[Indonesia]]. The three main dialects are Western Kamang, Lowland Kamang, and Upland Kamang. Dialects also include Lembur, Sibo, Kamang, Tiayai, Watang, Kamana-Kamang. They may constitute more than one language. Kamang is an [[endangered language]], since children usually only have passive competence of the language, and instead are shifting to [[Malay language|Malay]].<ref name=\"Schapper\" />\n\nSpeakers may prefer the term ''Kamang'' to refer to the speech community as a whole; ''Woisika'' is a village name.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://ausil.org.au/sites/ausil/files/1997%20Grimes%20etal%20Nusa%20Teng%20Guide.pdf|title=A guide to the people and languages of Nusa Tenggara|last=Grimes|first=Charles|publisher=Artha Wacana Press|year=1997|isbn=|location=Kupang|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Phonology==\n\n===Consonants===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=text-align:center\n|-\n|+Woisika consonant phonemes\n! colspan=2| \n! [[Labial consonant|Bilabial]]\n! [[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]]\n! [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]]\n! [[Velar consonant|Velar]]\n! [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]]\n|-\n! colspan=2| [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]]\n| {{IPAlink|m}}\n| {{IPAlink|n}}\n| \n| {{IPAlink|\u014b}} <ng>\n|\n|-\n! rowspan=2| [[Stop consonant|Plosive]]\n! <small>[[voicelessness|voiceless]]</small>\n| {{IPAlink|p}}\n| {{IPAlink|t}}\n|\n| {{IPAlink|k}}\n| ({{IPAlink|\u0294}}) <'>\n|-\n! <small>[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]</small>\n| {{IPAlink|b}}\n| {{IPAlink|d}}\n|\n| {{IPAlink|\u0261}}\n|\n|-\n! colspan=2| [[Fricative consonant|Fricative]]\n| {{IPAlink|\u0278}} <f>\n| {{IPAlink|s}}\n|\n|\n| ({{IPAlink|h}})\n|-\n! colspan=2| [[Approximant consonant|Approximant]]\n| {{IPAlink|w}}\n| \n| {{IPAlink|j}} <y>\n| \n|\n|-\n! colspan=2| [[Lateral consonant|Lateral]]\n| \n| {{IPAlink|l}}\n|\n| \n|\n|}\n\n/h/ and /\u0294/ are marginal. /r/ is rare in initial and final position. Word-final /s/ is only in loan words.\n\nThe consonant /\u014b/ is not found word-initially, and /f/ is not found word-finally.<ref name=\"Phonemics\">{{cite book |last1=Stokhof |first1=W.A.L. |title=Woisika II Phonemics |date=1979 |publisher=Australian National University|url=https://openresearch-repository.anu.edu.au/bitstream/1885/146505/1/PL-B59.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Vowels===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+caption | '''Woisika vowel phonemes'''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! \n! colspan=2 | [[Front vowel|Front]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Central vowel|Central]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Back vowel|Back]]\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Close vowel|Close]]\n| {{IPAlink|i}}\n| {{IPAlink|i\u02d0}} <ii>\n|colspan=2|\n| {{IPAlink|u}}\n| {{IPAlink|u\u02d0}} <uu>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Mid vowel|Mid]]\n| {{IPAlink|e}} \n| {{IPAlink|e\u02d0}} <ee> \n|colspan=2|\n| {{IPAlink|o}}\n| {{IPAlink|o\u02d0}} <oo> \n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[Open vowel|Open]]\n|colspan=2|\n| {{IPAlink|a}}\n| {{IPAlink|a\u02d0}} <aa> \n|colspan=2|\n|}\n\n==Grammar==\n\n===Serial Verb Constructions===\n\nKamang has [[serial verb construction]]s.\n\n:{| \n|''Mooi''||''bong''||''nok''||''kok''||''silang''||''dii''<ref name=\"Schapper\" />{{rp|345}}\n|-\n|banana||tree||one||fall.down||descend||lie\n|-\n|colspan=6|'A banana tree came falling down.'\n|}\n\n\n:{| \n|''Afunaa''||''yakii''||''me''||''noowaai.''<ref name=\"Schapper\" />{{rp|348}}\n|-\n|a-funaa||ga-kii||me||noo-waai.||\n|-\n|{{small|3.PAT}}-face||{{small|3.PAT}}-turn||come||{{small|3.AST}}-face\n|-\n|colspan=6|'Turn and face me.'\n|}\n\n===Valence===\n\nExamples with avalent, monovalent, bivalent, and trivalent verbs are shown below.<ref name=\"Schapper\">{{cite book |author1=Schapper, Antoinette |editor1-last=Schapper |editor1-first=Antoinette |title=The Papuan Languages of Timor, Alor and Pantar: Volume 1: Sketch Grammars |date=2014 |publisher=Walter de Gruyter |pages=287-349 |chapter=Kamang}}</ref>\n\nAvalent\n\n:{| \n|''Itunma''<ref name=\"Schapper\" />{{rp|300}}\n|-\n|itun-ma\n|-\n|late.afternoon-{{small|PFV}}\n|-\n|colspan=6|'It's late afternoon.'\n|}\n\nMonovalent\n\n:{| \n|''Markus''||''gamanteima''<ref name=\"Schapper\" />{{rp|301}}\n|-\n|Markus||ga-mantei-ma\n|-\n|Markus||{{small|3.PAT}}-thirst-{{small|PFV}}\n|-\n|colspan=6|'Markus is thirsty already.'\n|}\n\nBivalent\n\n:{| \n|''Na''||''Markus''||''gatakma.''<ref name=\"Schapper\" />{{rp|301}}\n|-\n|na||Markus||ga-tak-ma\n|-\n|{{small|1SG.AGT}}||Markus||{{small|3.PAT}}-see-{{small|PFV}}\n|-\n|colspan=6|'I have seen Markus'\n|}\n\nTrivalent\n\n:{| \n|''Markus''||''patei''||''me''||''dumma''||''wotulen.''<ref name=\"Schapper\" />{{rp|301}}\n|-\n|Markus||patei||me||dum=a||go-tulen\n|-\n|Markus||corn||{{small|TAKE}}||child={{small|SPEC}}||{{small|3.LOC}}-divide\n|-\n|colspan=6|'Markus divides corn amongst the children.'\n|}\n\n==Riddles==\nWoisika riddles relate to animals, the human body, human artifacts, natural phenomena, crops and other foods, among others.<ref name=\"Riddles\">{{cite book |last1=Stokhof |first1=W.A.L. |title=Woisika Riddles |date=1982 |publisher=Australian National University|url=https://openresearch-repository.anu.edu.au/bitstream/1885/145070/1/PL-D41.pdf}}</ref>\n\n