eurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111220155725/http://www.pakpost.gov.pk/postcode/postcode.html|archivedate=20 December 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| area_code_type                  = [[Dialling codes in Pakistan|Dialling code]]\n| area_code                       = 048<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ptcl.com.pk/Info/National-Dialing-Codes|title=National Dialing Codes|website=Ptcl.com.pk|accessdate=12 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151109145658/http://www.ptcl.com.pk/Info/National-Dialing-Codes|archive-date=9 November 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n| blank_name_sec1                 = Location\n| blank_info_sec1                 = *1,202 km (747 mi) North of [[Karachi]]<ref>https://www.rome2rio.com/s/Karachi/Sargodha</ref>\n*187 km (116 mi) West of [[Lahore]]<ref>https://www.distancecalculator.net/from-lahore-to-sargodha</ref>\n*241 km (150 mi) South of [[Islamabad]]<ref>https://www.distancesto.com/road-map/pk/sargodha-to-islamabad/history/598090.html</ref>\n*91 km (57 mi) NW of [[Faisalabad]]<ref>http://pk.toponavi.com/66794-66792</ref>\n*223 km (139 mi) South of [[Rawalpindi]]<ref>https://www.distancecalculator.net/from-rawalpindi-to-sargodha</ref>\n| blank_name_sec2                 = Number of [[Union councils of Pakistan|union councils]]\n| blank_info_sec2                 = 22\n| blank1_name_sec2                = Number of [[town]]s\n| blank1_info_sec2                = 59\n| website                         = {{URL|http://www.sargodha.gop.pk/}}; {{URL|http://cbs.gov.pk/}}; {{URL|http://www.tmasargodha.com/}}\n| official_name                   = \n| nickname                        = City of Eagles<ref>http://visitpak.com/useful-info-about-sargodha-pakistan-the-city-of-eagles/</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Sargodha''' ([[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] and {{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0633\u0631\u06af\u0648\u062f\u06be\u0627}}}}) is the [[List of most populous cities in Pakistan|11th largest]] city in [[Pakistan]].<ref name=\"citypopulation.de\">{{cite web|url=http://www.citypopulation.de/Pakistan-100T.html|title=Pakistan: Provinces and Major Cities \u2013 Population Statistics, Maps, Charts, Weather and Web Information|website=Citypopulation.de}}</ref> It is also an administrative centre of [[Sargodha Division]] located in the [[Punjab (Pakistan)|Punjab]] province, Pakistan and one of the fastest growing cities in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ghar47.com/2015/07/05/commercial-real-estate-property-in-sargodha-pakistan/|title=Commercial Real Estate Property in Sargodha Pakistan \u2013 Ghar47|work=Ghar47|accessdate=12 March 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216175421/http://ghar47.com/2015/07/05/commercial-real-estate-property-in-sargodha-pakistan/|archivedate=16 February 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sargodha is also known as ''City of Eagles''.<ref>http://visitpak.com/useful-info-about-sargodha-pakistan-the-city-of-eagles/</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Late 19th Century House.jpg|thumb|19th century House in Sargodha]]\n[[File:Shah Shams Sherazi -Mausoleum.jpg|thumb|Mausoleum of Hazrat Shah Shams Sherazi]]\nSargodha was established by the British as a canal-colony in 1903, and was initially spelt Sargoda.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wkBuAAAAMAAJ&q=sargodha+history+1903&dq=sargodha+history+1903&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjUkMy77KzZAhVkHGMKHcVgCvgQ6AEIKTAB|title=Pakistan: a historical and cultural panorama|last=Masud|first=Tariq|date=1989|publisher=Al-Waqar Publishers|isbn=9789698054021|language=en}}</ref> Sargodha was badly affected by an outbreak of the plague in 1903, and experienced a milder outbreak in 1904.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K5LX9AUcyMYC&pg=PA26&dq=sargodha+history+1903&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjUkMy77KzZAhVkHGMKHcVgCvgQ6AEIPTAF#v=onepage&q=sargodha%20history%201903&f=false|title=Hailey: A Study in British Imperialism, 1872\u20131969|last=Cell|first=John W.|last2=Cell|first2=John Whitson|date=2002-08-22|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=9780521521178|language=en}}</ref> Although it was a small town in the beginning, the British [[Royal Air Force]] built an airport here due to its strategic location.<ref name=\"sargodha.dc.lhc.gov.pk\">{{cite web|url=http://sargodha.dc.lhc.gov.pk/?page_id=1335|title=District Website|website=Lhc.gov.pk}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n===Location===\nSargodha is located {{convert|172|km}} northwest of [[Lahore]], in [[Sargodha District]]. It lies about {{convert|30|mile|order=flip}} from the M-2 motorway, which connects Lahore and Islamabad. It is connected to the M-2 by several interchanges at different locations. Sargodha is roughly {{cvt|94|km}} from [[Faisalabad]], due southeast. Directly east connected by the M-2 motorway are Lahore and the route to Rawalpindi and Islamabad. Due east is the city of Jhang; toward the west are the city of Mianwali and the Chashma Barrage. Dera Ismail Khan is located {{cvt|232|km}} southwest from the city.\n\n===Topography===\nSargodha mainly comprises flat, fertile plains, although here are a few small hills on the Sargodha-Faisalabad Road. The River Jhelum flows on the western and northern sides, and the River [[Chenab]] lies on the eastern side of the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sargodha.gop.pk/district-at-glance|title=District at Glance|work=sargodha.gop.pk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150626122455/http://www.sargodha.gop.pk/district-at-glance|archivedate=26 June 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The city is located 190 metres above sea level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldatlas.com/as/pk/pb/where-is-sargodha.html|title=Where is Sargodha, Pakistan?|website=WorldAtlas.com|language=en|access-date=2018-02-17}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nThe city has a climate of extreme heat in the summers and moderate cold in the winters. The maximum temperature reaches {{convert|50|C}} in the summer while the minimum temperature recorded is as low as freezing point in the winter.\n\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n| location     = Sargodha (1960\u20132012)\n| metric first = y\n| single line  = y\n| Jan high C = 20\n| Feb high C = 22\n| Mar high C = 26\n| Apr high C = 32\n| May high C = 38\n| Jun high C = 39\n| Jul high C = 38\n| Aug high C = 37\n| Sep high C = 36\n| Oct high C = 32\n| Nov high C = 26\n| Dec high C = 22\n| year high C = 30.6\n| Jan low C = 8\n| Feb low C = 11\n| Mar low C = 15.5\n| Apr low C = 19\n| May low C = 25\n| Jun low C = 27\n| Jul low C = 26\n| Aug low C = 26\n| Sep low C = 25\n| Oct low C = 20\n| Nov low C = 14\n| Dec low C = 9\n| year low C = 18.8\n| Jan precipitation mm = 18\n| Feb precipitation mm = 36\n| Mar precipitation mm = 24\n| Apr precipitation mm = 13\n| May precipitation mm = 17\n| Jun precipitation mm = 48\n| Jul precipitation mm = 82\n| Aug precipitation mm = 87\n| Sep precipitation mm = 43\n| Oct precipitation mm = 9\n| Nov precipitation mm = 11\n| Dec precipitation mm = 12\n| Jan precipitation days = 5\n| Feb precipitation days = 4\n| Mar precipitation days = 5\n| Apr precipitation days = 4\n| May precipitation days = 3\n| Jun precipitation days = 3\n| Jul precipitation days = 7\n| Aug precipitation days = 7\n| Sep precipitation days = 4\n| Oct precipitation days = 1\n| Nov precipitation days = 1\n| Dec precipitation days = 1\n| unit precipitation days = 1.0 mm\n| source 1                = Weather2,<ref name = Weather2>\n{{cite web\n  |url=http://www.myweather2.com/City-Town/Pakistan/Sargodha/climate-profile.aspx\n  | title = Weather2 \u2013 Sargodha\n  | accessdate =8 July 2012\n}}</ref>\n| date                    = August 2010\n}}\n\n==Demographics==\nTotal population of the city was 458,440<ref name=\"census.gov.pk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pbs.gov.pk/sites/default/files//tables/POPULATION%20SIZE%20AND%20GROWTH%20OF%20MAJOR%20CITIES.pdf |title=Population size and growth of major cities |publisher=[[Pakistan Bureau of Statistics]] |date=1998}}</ref> according to the 1998 census.  The majority of the people in the city speak [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]].<ref name=\"sargodha.dc.lhc.gov.pk\"/> According to the census of 2017, the population of City was recorded 659,862<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypopulation.de/Pakistan-100T.html|title=Pakistan: Provinces and Major Cities \u2013 Population Statistics, Maps, Charts, Weather and Web Information|website=www.citypopulation.de}}</ref> with the rise of 43.94% while the population of metropolitan area (City District) reached 3,903,588 out of which 1 million forms the urban population.<ref name=\"DISTRICT WISE CENSUS RESULTS CENSUS 2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|title=DISTRICT WISE CENSUS RESULTS CENSUS 2017|publisher=www.pbscensus.gov.pk|access-date=2017-09-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829164748/http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> The population of [[Sargodha Division]] was recorded as 8,181,499 as per [[2017 Census of Pakistan]]\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Mall of Sargodha.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Mall of Sargodha under construction]]\nMajority of economy of Sargodha depends upon agriculture. Sargodha is considered as the best citrus producing area of Pakistan and therefore, it is also known as [[California]] of Pakistan.<ref>www.historypak.com/sargodha/</ref> Sargodha is largest [[Kinnow]] producing district of the world. It produces best quality oranges and supply to the different parts of the country. These oranges are also exported to other countries and contributes to the economy of Pakistan.<ref>https://www.academia.edu/7790985/Orange_Economy_of_Sargodha</ref> Sargodha also produces a huge amount of wheat, cotton, rice and vegetables that are transported to other parts of country and also exported to other countries. \n\nThere are also Textile mills, Rice processing plants and juice factories of [[Nestle]] and [[Shezan]].<ref>www.historypak.com/sargodha/</ref>\n\nThe Sargodha Chamber of Commerce and Industry monitors industrial activity in the city and reports their findings to the [[Federation of Pakistan Chamber of Commerce and Industry]] and provincial government.<ref>https://www.scci.pk</ref> Dry port is also under construction in Sargodha.<ref>https://tribune.com.pk/story/1111172/facilitating-exports-dry-port-established-sargodha/</ref>\n\n[[File:Burj Ismail Mall Sargodha.jpg|thumb|250px|Burj Ismail Mall]]\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Rehman Trade Centre Sargodha.jpg|thumb|250px|Rehman Trade Centre located on University Road]] -->\n\nThere are also several shopping malls and trade centres in the city that have a presence of international and national brands. Some of them are as follow:<ref>\nhttp://www.mallofsargodha.com</ref>\n*Mall of Sargodha\n*Burj Ismail Mall\n*Chenone Tower\n*Rehman Trade Centre\n*Burj Huraira Mall\n*Trust Plaza\n*Galaxy Mobile Tower\n*Toheed Mall\n*Apna Cash & Carry\n*Dreamland Shopping Mall\n*Shaheen Shopping Mall\n*Modern Shopping Mall\n*Punjab Mega Mall\n\n\nFifteen bazaars (markets) of Sargodha remain a major trading zone in the city. Each of the fifteen bazaars has a particular name and is known for selling certain goods as follows:<ref>https://pmbmc.punjab.gov.pk/sargodha</ref><ref name=\"urbanunit.gov.pk\">http://www.urbanunit.gov.pk/PublicationDocs/Punjab%20city%20profiles/Sargodha%20City%20Profile.pdf</ref>\n*Model Bazaar contains food court, joyland and shops of grocery and garments.\n*Urdu Bazaar contains shops of stationery and books.\n*Kachehry Bazaar contains bakeries, street food restaurants and shops of shoes, garments and general stores.\n*Amin Bazaar contains shops of fabrics, boutique], garments and electric appliances.\n*Muslim Bazaar contains sanitary items and motorcycle repair shops.\n*Anarkali Bazaar contains shops of each and every household items.\n*Sarafa Bazaar contains gold and jewellery shops.\n*Rail Bazaar contains shops of fabrics.\n*Liaquat Bazaar provides shops for new bicycles and sports cycles.\n*Faisal Bazar provides shops for spices, oil, meat and poultry.\n*Karkhana Bazaar provides shops for crockery and cutlery products.\n*Bans Bazaar supplies dairy and milk products.\n*Kabaarhi Bazaar contains shops of [[brokers]].\n*Fruit Mandi is a fruit market.\n*Sabzi Mandi is a vegetable, meat, fish and grocery market.\n\n==Administration==\nSargodha is the capital of [[Sargodha Tehsil]]. As of October 2012, the division system in Punjab Province has been restored and Sargodha became the divisional headquarters of districts [[Sargodha District|Sargodha]], [[Khushab District|Khushab]], [[Mianwali District|Mianwali]] and [[Bhakkar District|Bhakkar]]. Sargodha became the administrative capital of the [[Sargodha Division]] handling over a population of about 8.1 Million.<ref name=\"DISTRICT WISE CENSUS RESULTS CENSUS 2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|title=DISTRICT WISE CENSUS RESULTS CENSUS 2017|publisher=www.pbscensus.gov.pk|access-date=2017-09-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829164748/http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Municipal Committee of Sargodha city was upgraded into Municipal Corporation in 1981 when the population of city was increased over half a million.<ref>http://tmasargodha.lgpunjab.org.pk</ref> Sargodha Municipal Corporation is administratively subdivided into 22 [[Union councils of Pakistan|union councils]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nrb.gov.pk/lg_election/union.asp?district=32&dn=Sargodha |title=Tehsils & Unions in the District of Sargodha \u2013 Government of Pakistan |website=Nrb.gov.pk |accessdate=2012-03-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120209043409/http://www.nrb.gov.pk/lg_election/union.asp?district=32&dn=Sargodha |archivedate=9 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Safe City Project===\n\nSargodha was announced as one of six cities in Punjab whose security would be improved by the [[Punjab Safe Cities Authority]]. 5.5 billion Rupees have been allocated for the project,<ref>{{cite news|title=After Lahore, six others to become 'safer cities'|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1332499/lahore-six-others-become-safer-cities/|accessdate=23 February 2017|agency=Express Tribune|date=20 February 2017}}</ref> which will be modeled along the lines of the Lahore Safe City project in which 8,000 [[CCTV]] cameras were installed throughout the city at a cost of 12 billion rupees to record and send images to Integrated Command and Control Centres.<ref>{{cite news|title=Punjab Safe City Project inaugurated|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1289650|accessdate=23 February 2017|agency=Dawn|date=12 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Healthcare==\n[[File:DHQ Teaching hospital Sargodha.jpg|thumb|centre|350px|DHQ Teaching Hospital is the largest hospital of Sargodha.]]\n\n[[File:Mubarak Hospital Sargodha.jpg|thumb|Mubarak Medical Complex]]\n===Hospitals===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! [[Hospital]]<ref>https://www.marham.pk/hospitals/sargodha</ref>\n! Type\n! [[Location]]\n|-\n| DHQ Teaching Hospital\n| [[Public]]\n| [[Mianwali]] Road\n|-\n| Mubarak Medical Complex\n| [[Private hospital|Private]]\n| [[Fatima Jinnah]] Road\n|-\n| [[Combined Military Hospital]]\n| [[Army]]\n| Sargodha Garrison\n|-\n| Fatima Hospital\n| Private\n| [[University of Sargodha|University]] Road\n|-\n| Niazi Medical Complex\n| Private\n| Club Road\n|-\n| Rai Medical Complex\n| Private\n| [[Fatima Jinnah]] Road\n|-\n| Sadiq Hospital\n| Private\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n|-\n| [[Civil Hospital]]\n| [[Public]]\n| [[Mianwali]] Road\n|-\n| Khawaja Arshad Hospital\n| Private\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n|-\n| City Hospital\n| Private\n| Zafrullah Road\n|-\n| Central Hospital\n| Private\n| [[Sargodha Cricket Stadium|Stadium]] Road\n|-\n| Rabia International Hospital\n| Private\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n|-\n| [[PAF Hospitals|PAF Hospital]]\n| [[Air force]]\n| [[PAF Base Mushaf]]\n|-\n| [[Fauji Foundation|Fauji Foundation Hospital]]\n| [[Army]]\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n|-\n| Rafiqa Medical Hospital\n| Private\n| Block no. 12, Muslim Bazar\n|-\n| Kazmi Hospital\n| Private\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n|-\n| Saba VIP Hospital\n| Private\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n|-\n| Sarwar Hospital\n| Private\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n|-\n| Tayyab Medicare Hospital\n| Private\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n|-\n| Tufail Hospital\n| Private\n| Pull 11, [[Faisalabad]] Road\n|-\n| Munir Hospital\n| Private\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n|-\n| [[Hilal Ahmar|Halal-e-Ahmar Hospital]]\n| [[Public]]\n| Satellite Town B-Block\n|-\n| Fatima Nazir Memorial Hospital\n| Private\n| [[University of Sargodha|University]] Road\n|-\n| [[University of Sargodha|University Medical and Research Centre]]\n| [[Public]]\n| [[University of Sargodha]]\n|-\n| Abdullah Medical Complex\n| Private\n| [[Sargodha Cricket Stadium|Stadium]] Road\n|-\n| Al-Abbas Hospital\n| Private\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n|-\n| Al-Rasheed Hospital\n| Private\n| [[Bahadur Shah Zafar]] Road\n|-\n| Bajwa Trauma Centre\n| Private\n| [[Sargodha Cricket Stadium|Stadium]] Road\n|-\n| Bhatti Medical Complex\n| Private\n| 49-Tail, [[Faisalabad]] Road\n|-\n| Butcha Hospital\n| Private\n| Satellite Town B-block\n|-\n| Cheema Heart Centre\n| Private\n| [[Bahadur Shah Zafar]] Road\n|-\n| Ibrahim Hospital\n| Private\n| [[Bahadur Shah Zafar]] Road\n|-\n| Millat Orthopaedic Complex\n| Private\n| [[Sargodha Cricket Stadium|Stadium]] Road\n|-\n| Mushtaq Medical Imaging Hospital\n| Private\n| [[Fatima Jinnah]] Road\n|-\n| Niazi Medical Tower\n| Private\n| [[Mianwali]] Road\n|-\n| National Hospital\n| Private\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n|-\n| Riaz Hospital\n| Private\n| 49-Tail, [[Faisalabad]] Road\n|-\n| Shifa Hospital\n| Private\n| [[Mianwali]] Road\n|-\n| Shafi Hospital\n| Private\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n|-\n| Wajahat Hospital\n| Private\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n|-\n| Zaheer Laser Eye Centre\n| Private\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n|-\n|}\n\n==Education==\n[[File:UoS.jpg|thumb|Main Gate to University of Sargodha]]\n[[File:PAF Public School Sargodha HQ 2003.jpg|thumb|PAF Public School]]\n\nAccording to the census of 1998, the literacy rate of [[Sargodha]] city was 67.8% while in 2017 the literacy rate was recorded as 80.5% with a rapid increase in few years.<ref>https://www.urbanunit.gov.pk \u203a ...PDF\nSargodha City Profile \u2013 The Urban Unit</ref> The city is considered as the educational hub of Sargodha Division handling the population of about 8.1 million.<ref name=\"DISTRICT WISE CENSUS RESULTS CENSUS 2017\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|title=DISTRICT WISE CENSUS RESULTS CENSUS 2017|publisher=www.pbscensus.gov.pk|access-date=2017-09-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829164748/http://www.pbscensus.gov.pk/sites/default/files/DISTRICT_WISE_CENSUS_RESULTS_CENSUS_2017.pdf|archive-date=2017-08-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Sargodha Division]] has its own Education Board for Secondary School Certificate (SSC) & Higher Secondary School Certificate (HSSC) Examinations. There are about 4 universities and numerous colleges of Medical Sciences, Law, IT, Commerce, Engineering and Intermediate Courses.\n\n\n=== Board of Intermediate and Secondary Education Sargodha ===\nBoard of Intermediate & Secondary Education, Sargodha<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bisesargodha.edu.pk|title=BISE SARGODHA}}</ref> handles the whole Sargodha Division that includes 4 districts (Sargodha, Mianwali, Khushab & Bhakkar). It was established in 1968 under the West Pakistan Board of Intermediate & Secondary Education ([[Board of Intermediate and Secondary Education, Multan|Multan]] and [[Board of Intermediate and Secondary Education, Sargodha]]) Ordinance No. VII of 1968, with the jurisdiction of Sargodha and Rawalpindi Civil Divisions.\n\n=== Colleges and Universities ===\n{{Main|List of colleges and universities in Sargodha}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|-\n! University/College\n! Type\n! Location\n! Established\n! Website\n|-\n| [[University of Sargodha]]\n| [[Public]]\n| University Road\n| 2002\n|<ref>https://www.uos.edu.pk</ref>\n|-\n| [[University College of Agriculture]]\n| [[Public]]\n| Sargodha Bypass near Jhal Chakian\n| 2002\n|\n|-\n| [[University of Lahore|University of Lahore, Sargodha Campus]]\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Lahore Road\n| 2002\n|<ref>https://www.uol.edu.pk/about-us</ref>\n|-\n| [[University of Central Punjab|University of Central Punjab, Sargodha Campus]]\n|[[Private university|Private]]\n|Lahore Road\n|2002\n|<ref>https://www.ucp.edu.pk</ref>\n|-\n| [[Sargodha Medical College]]\n| [[Public]]\n| Faisalabad Road\n| 2006\n|<ref>https://www.uos.edu.pk/department/profile/14</ref>\n|-\n| [[Army Public Schools & Colleges System|Army Public College]]\n| [[Army]]\n| Mianwali Road\n| 1975\n|\n|-\n| [[Cornelius Law College]]\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Fatima Jinnah Road\n| 2015\n|<ref>http://pu.edu.pk/affiliation/collegeinfo/1270/Cornelius-Law-College-Lahore-Road-Sargodha</ref>\n|-\n| [[Quaid-e-Azam Law College]]\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Lahore Road\n| 1998 \n|<ref>https://qlc.edu.pk/sargodha-campus/</ref>\n|-\n| [[Punjab College of Science]]\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Khayaban-e-Sadiq (Main Campus)\n| 1985\n|<ref>https://www.pgc.edu/about-pgc</ref>\n|-\n| [[The Superior College]]\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n| 2000\n|<ref>https://superiorcolleges.edu.pk/sargodha/</ref>                            \n|-\n| [[Sargodha Institute of Technology]]\n| \n| University Road\n| 1927\n| {{cn|date=March 2020}}\n|-\n| ILM College\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Satellite Town A-Block\n| 2008\n|<ref>http://ilm.edu.pk/campuses.php</ref>\n|-\n| Rai Medical College\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Bhalwal Road\n| 2013\n|<ref>www.pmdc.org.pk \u203a profilePDF\n\u2022 Name of College Rai Medical College, Sargodha Address Near 33 Phatak Islamabad ...</ref>\n|-\n| Niazi Medical and Dental College\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Lahore Road\n| 2017\n|<ref>http://www.nmdc.edu.pk</ref>\n|-\n| Airbase Inter College \n| [[Air Force]]\n| Jail Road\n| 1981\n|\n|-\n| Fazaia Inter College\n| [[Air Force]]\n| [[PAF Base Mushaf]]\n| 1981\n|\n|-\n| Iqra Girls College\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| University Road\n| 2009\n| <ref>http://www.iqragirlscollege.edu.pk</ref>\n|-\n| National College of Business Administration & Economics, [[Sargodha]] Campus \n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Railway Road\n| 2014\n|<ref>http://ncbae.edu.pk</ref>\n|-\n| The Reader College\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Khayaban-e-Sadiq\n| 2016\n|<ref>http://www.reader.edu.pk</ref>\n|-\n| Government Ambala Muslim College\n| [[Public]]\n| Kot Fareed Road\n| 1947\n| <ref>https://www.punjab.gov.pk/pc_sargodha</ref>\n|-\n| Government College of Commerce\n| [[Public]]\n| Faisalabad Road\n| 1950\n|\n|-\n| Government Postgraduate College for Women, Chandani Chowk\n| [[Public]]\n| Chandani Chowk\n| 1962\n| <ref>https://www.punjab.gov.pk/pc_sargodha</ref>\n|-\n| Government Degree College for Women, Block no. 23\n| [[Public]]\n| Block no. 23\n| 1975\n| <ref>https://www.punjab.gov.pk/pc_sargodha</ref>\n|-\n| Government College for Women, Farooq Colony\n| [[Public]]\n| Farooq Colony\n| 1975\n| <ref>https://www.punjab.gov.pk/pc_sargodha</ref>\n|-\n| Acme College of Excellence\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Faisalabad Road\n| 2004\n|<ref>https://fbise.edu.pk/inst-record.php?name=2822</ref>\n|-\n| Hira Polytechnic College\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Fatima Jinnah Road\n| 2014\n|<ref>http://hiracollegesargodha.edu.pk</ref>\n|-\n| Sargodha Institute of Health Sciences\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Satellite Town C-Block\n| 2016\n|<ref>http://www.sihs.edu.pk</ref>\n|-\n| IT Hub\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Stadium Road\n| 2015\n|<ref>http://www.ithub.edu.pk</ref>\n|-\n| Misali Ravian College\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Satellite Town A-block\n| 2000s\n|\n|-\n| Hanif College of Accountancy\n| [[Private university|Private]]\n| Satellite Town A-block\n| 2012\n|<ref>http://hca.com.pk</ref>\n|-\n|ITM College\n|[[Private university|Private]]\n|University Road\n|2000\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Schools===\n[[File:PAF public school Sargodha.jpg|thumb|PAF Public School, Sargodha]]\n{{See|List of educational institutes in Sargodha}}\n\n==Transportation==\n===Road===\n[[File:University Road, Sargodha.jpg|thumb|left|225px|University Road, Sargodha]]\n[[File:Khayyam Chowk Flyover Sargodha.jpg|thumb|left|225px|Khayyam Chowk Flyover]]\n'''Main Roads'''\n\n3.5 km University Roads runs from 47 Pull to Khayyam Chowk. Other main roads include Fatima Jinnah Road, Canal Road, Katchery Road, Khushab Road (Mianwalli Road), Sillanwali Road, Bhalwal Road and Shaheenabad Road etc.\n\n'''Highways'''\n\nSargodha lies about {{Convert|30|mi|km}} from the [[M-2 motorway (Pakistan)|M-2 Motorway]] which connects Lahore and [[Islamabad]]. [[N-60 National Highway]] runs from Sargodha to Lahore through [[Pindi Bhattian]] and [[Sheikhupura]]. It is also connected to Faisalabad by a highway.\n\n'''Buses'''\n\nGeneral Bus Stand is located on Fatima Jinnah Road. [[Daewoo Express|Daewoo Bus Service]] drives regular routes from Sargodha to the rest of the country.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.daewoo.com.pk/terminal_view.asp?menu_set=5&submenu_set=1&page_title=Sargodha&terminal_code=13 |title=Archived copy |access-date=6 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706175300/http://www.daewoo.com.pk/terminal_view.asp?menu_set=5&submenu_set=1&page_title=Sargodha&terminal_code=13 |archive-date=6 July 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Others include Niazi Express, Faisal Movers, Bilal Travels, Islamabad Express and Skyways etc.\n[[File: Motorway Sargodha.jpg|thumb|Motorway M2 entering district Sargodha]]\n[[File: M2 Sargodha.jpg|thumb|Motorway M2 exit to Sargodha]]\n\n'''Taxi/Cab and Rikshaws'''\n\n\n\nOnline cab services [[Uber]] and [[Careem]] are also available in the city.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.careem.com/en-ae/cities/|title=Countries of Operation|language=en}}</ref> Moreover many Rikshaws are also available throughout the city which are more economical.\n\n===Rail===\nSargodha is also connected by the rest of the country through the rail.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railpk.com/sarghodha.html|title=Pakistan Railway Time Table|work=railpk.com}}</ref> [[Sargodha Junction railway station]] is located on Shorkot-Lala Musa branch railway line.\n\n== Air Base==\nPakistan's largest [[airbase]], [[PAF Base Mushaf]] (formerly PAF Base Sargodha), is situated in Sargodha and hosts the headquarters of the [[Pakistan Air Force]]'s Central Air Command. The airbase is also home to the Combat Commanders School (CCS), formerly the Fighter Leader's School.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glowpakistan.com/about-pakistan/About-Sargodha-292|title=About Sargodha|work=glowpakistan.com}}</ref>\n\n==Recreation==\n{{multiple image\n |align=centre\n |width=250\n |image1=Company Bagh Sargodha2.jpg\n |caption1=Centre of famous Company Bagh\n |alt1=Centre of famous Company Bagh\n |image2=Company Bagh Sargodha3.jpg\n |caption2=Antique Fighter Jet mounted in Company Bagh\n |alt2=Antique Fighter Jet mounted in Company Bagh\n}}\n===Points of Interest===\n====Kirana Hills====\n[[File:Kirana Hills Lake Sargodha.jpg|thumb|Lake of Kirana Hills]]\nThe [[Kirana Hills]] is a small and extensive rocky [[mountain range]] located in Sargodha.<ref>{{harv|Mahajan|2009|pp=100\u2013110}}</ref><ref>{{harv|Ali|2002|pp=25\u201326}}</ref><ref>{{harv|Smith|2007|pp=92\u201393}}</ref><ref name=Wikimaps>{{cite web |last1=Wikimaps |title=Kirana Hills |url=http://wikimapia.org/12771852/Kirana-Hills |website=Wikimapia.org |accessdate=14 June 2015}}</ref> It is also a place of tourist attraction in Sargodha City. Locally known as \"'''Black Mountains'''\"<ref name=\"Bahria University press\">{{cite web |last1=DoE&ES |first1=Department of Earth and Environmental Sciences |title=Special report: Field report on Kirana Hills |url=http://www.slideshare.net/chsabasaif/slideshare-29477895 |publisher=Bahria University Press |accessdate=15 June 2015 |location=Karachi, Sindh, Pakistan |pages=33 |language=English |format=.net| ref = harv |date=2012}}</ref> due to its [[Bistre|brownish landscape]], its highest peak is about {{convert|980|ft|m}}.<ref>{{harv|DoE&ES|2012|pp=4\u20135}}</ref>\n\n====Jinnah Hall====\n[[File:Jinnah Hall Sargodha.jpg|thumb|left|Jinnah Hall, Sargodha]]\n[[Jinnah Hall]] is a historical landmark and point of interest in Sargodha.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Jinnah+Hall/@32.0830934,72.6661648,15z/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x0:0xcf178cb476e5cada?sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj3io3WjJTPAhVFExoKHSyXAbUQ_BIIYTAO |title=Google Maps |website=Google.com |date= |accessdate=2016-09-17}}</ref> Jinnah Hall was built in 1949. It was named for the Founder of Pakistan, [[Muhammad Ali Jinnah]]. Jinnah Hall was built originally as a town hall and library in Company Bagh, Sargodha but now currently used as an exhibition hall, event space, and library.\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Hockey Stadium Sargodha.jpg|thumb|centre|350px|Sargodha Astroturf Hockey Stadium located near [[Mela Mandi Ground]]]]\nSargodha is home to the [[Sargodha Cricket Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan/content/ground/59014.html|title=Sports Stadium \u2013 Pakistan \u2013 Cricket Grounds \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|work=Cricinfo}}</ref> Sargodha cricket team were a first-class cricket team that represented Sargodha Division in Punjab Province in Pakistan. They competed in Pakistan's first-class tournaments between 1961\u201362 and 2002\u201303. [[Mela Mandi Ground]] is a multi-use historic stadium in Sargodha.  It is currently used mostly for [[cricket]] and [[football (soccer)|football]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Mela+Mandi+Ground/@32.0691594,72.6590951,15z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x0:0x3d77fd98247eb21f!8m2!3d32.0691594!4d72.6590951%3C|title=Google Maps|website=Google Maps}}</ref> The Mela Mandi Ground was constructed to provide a vast ground for outdoor sports and activities. During March every year which is the country's spring season, several competitions are held here. Almost all Pakistani people join these annual games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.flighthub.com/cheap-flights-to-Sargodha|title=Cheap flights to Sargodha|website=Flighthub.com}}</ref>\n[[File:Mela Mandi Ground Sargodha.jpg|thumb|Annual Tent Pegging Competition held in Mela Mandi Ground]]\n\nSargodha is also home to Sargodha Astroturf Hockey Stadium located near Mela Mandi Ground. It is home to Sargodha District Hockey Team and provides a reliable platform for youngsters.<ref>https://www.urdupoint.com/en/sports/trials-for-hockey-team-selection-at-astroturf-539537.html</ref> Galaxy Sports Complex is a renowned Sports Academy of the city. <ref>http://wikimapia.org/3443348/Galaxy-ground</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n===Food and drink===\n[[File:Food street Sargodha.jpg|thumb|left|Food Street located on Stadium Road, Sargodha.]]\nCuisine of Sargodha is similar to that of other regions of South Asia, with some of it being originated from the royal kitchens of 16th-century Mughal emperors.<ref name=\"Goodwin2002\">{{cite book|last=Goodwin|first=William|title=Pakistan|year=2002|publisher=Lucent Books|language=English|isbn=978-1-59018-218-5|page=79|quote=Pakistani food is similar to that of northern India, with a splash of Middle Eastern influence derived from other Muslim cultures over the centuries.}}</ref> Most of those dishes have their roots in [[British cuisine|British]], [[Indian cuisine|Indian]], [[Central Asian cuisine|Central Asian]] and [[Middle Eastern cuisine]].<ref name=\"LeeNadeau2011\">{{cite book|last1=Lee|first1=Jonathan H.X.|last2=Nadeau|first2=Kathleen M.|title=Encyclopedia of Asian American Folklore and Folklife|year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|language=English|isbn=978-0-313-35066-5|page=[https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofas00leej/page/973 973]|quote=Pakistani cuisine\u2014a fusion of Central Asian, Middle Eastern, Persian, and Indian traditions\u2014is known for being spicy and for its aromatic and flavorful richness.|url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofas00leej/page/973}}</ref> Unlike Middle Eastern cuisine, Pakistani cooking uses large quantities of spices, herbs, and seasoning. Garlic, [[ginger]], [[turmeric]], red [[Chili powder|chili]], and [[garam masala]] are used in most dishes, and home cooking regularly includes curry, [[pita bread|''roti'']], a thin flatbread made from wheat, is a staple food, usually served with curry, meat, vegetables, and lentils. Rice is also common; it is served plain, fried with spices, and in sweet dishes.<ref name=\"yasmeen\">{{cite book |author=Yasmeen Niaz Mohiuddin |title=Pakistan: a global studies handbook |year=2006 |publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-85109-801-9|pages=3, 317, 323\u2013324}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Kathleen W. Deady |title=Countries of the world :Pakistan |year=2001 |publisher=Capstone Press |isbn=978-0-7368-0815-6 |pages=13\u201315}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=American Geriatrics Society. Ethnogeriatrics Committee |title=Doorway thoughts: cross-cultural health care for older adults |year=2006 |publisher=Jones & Bartlett Learning |isbn=978-0-7637-4355-0 |pages=119\u2013120}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Chili Chutney Restaurant Sargodha.jpg|thumb|A local restaurant in Sargodha]]\n\n[[Lassi]] is a traditional drink in the whole [[Punjab region]] including Sargodha Division. [[Pakistani tea culture|Black tea with milk and sugar]] is also popular throughout the city and is consumed daily by most of the population.<ref name=\"taxila\">{{cite book |title=Pakistan & the Karakoram Highway |year=2008 |publisher=Lonely Planet |isbn=978-1-74104-542-0 |pages=60, 128, 376 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zn8I4qEew9oC|author1=Sarina Singh |author2=Lindsay Brow |author3=Paul Clammer |author4=Rodney Cocks |author5=John Mock}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Tarla Dalal |title=Punjabi Khana |year=2007 |publisher=Sanjay & Co |isbn=978-81-89491-54-3 |page=8}}</ref>\n\n[[File:KFC Sargodha.jpg|thumb|left|250px|[[KFC]] outlet located on University Road, Sargodha]]\n[[File:McDonald's Sargodha.jpg|thumb|left|250px|[[McDonald's]] outlet in Sargodha]]\n\nIn addition to the traditional food, fast food is also very famous across the city.<ref>https://nation.com.pk/17-Dec-2017/the-fried-chicken-turnaround</ref> Along with local fast food restaurants, there is also a presence of outlets of many International Fast Food Restaurants in the city that includes [[KFC]], [[McDonald's]] and [[Pizza Hut]].<ref>https://www.kfcpakistan.com</ref><ref>https://mcdonalds.com.pk</ref><ref>https://www.pizzahut.com.pk</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{sisterlinks|Sargodha}}\n* [[Ali Haider Noor Khan Niazi]], politician \n* [[Feroz Khan Noon]], former [[Prime Minister of Pakistan|Prime Minister Pakistan]]\n* [[Anwer Ali Noon]], former Parliamentarian of Pakistan and army Officer\n* [[Amjad Ali Noon]], former Ambassador/High Commissioner of Pakistan\n* [[Imtiaz Bhatti]], former Ambassador / High Commissioner of Pakistan\n* [[Wazir Agha]], Urdu Scholar\n* [[Hameed Gul]], former ISI Chief\n* [[Ch. Anwar Ali Cheema]], politician, PML-Q\n* Ch.[[Ghias Mela]], politician, PML-Q\n* [[Hafiz Muhammad Saeed]], Amir [[Jama'at-ud-Da'wah]]\n* [[Mohammad Hafeez]], cricketer\n* [[Aizaz Cheema]], cricketer\n* [[Rafiq Anjum]], actor\n* [[Farhat Hashmi]], Islamic Scholar\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Neighbourhoods of Sargodha}}\n\n[[Category:Metropolitan areas of Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Planned cities in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Sargodha]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the